<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 16:00 GMT October 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Moscow Prosecutor's Office has initiated criminal
proceedings against ex-deputy prime minister and former head of
the State Property Committee Alfred Kokh on a charge of abuse of
office, the Interfax news agency reported
today. (Russia-Kokh-Criminal Proceedings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canadian economy surged in July, erasing concerns of
a slowdown signaled by flat numbers in June, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada reported Tuesday that the country's gross
domestic product (GDP) grew by 0.8 percent in July, doubling the
pace of growth forecasters had been expecting. (Canada-GDP-July)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Unemployment remains a serious problem for the
European Union (EU) whose jobless rate stood at 10.8 percent in
mid-1997, said an employment report issued today by the European
Commission, the EU's executive body. (EU-Unemployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MAASTRICHT -- NATO defense ministers will hold a two-day talk
on when and how to phase out the presence in Bosnia-Herzegovina of
SFOR troops whose peacekeeping mandate expires in June,
1998. (NATO-Defense Ministers-Bosnia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Major South Korean conglomerates and their
organizations welcomed the government's Tuesday decision to
amnesty 23 business tycoons sentenced for bribing former President
Roh Tae-woo.(Skorea-Tycoons-Amnesty)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Public approval rating for Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto's cabinet plunged 12 percentage points to 44.1
percent, the lowest since his first cabinet was formed in January
1996, a survey released by a leading Japanese newspaper
said. (Japan-Hashimoto-Support Rate)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Gary Locke, the first Chinese-American elected
governor in the United States, is starting a journey back to his
ancestral home this week.
</P>
<P>
Locke, the Washington governor, will be accompanied by his
parents, brother and several sisters to his ancestral village of
Jilong in Guangdong province, which will become the highlight of
his 12-day Asia trip starting on Wednesday. (US-China-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama placed the provinces of Chiriqui and
Bocas del Toro on alert for hemorrhagic dengue fever after two
people were killed by the disease in the neighboring Costa Rican
town of Punta Arenas Tuesday. (Panama-Dengue)  
</P>
