<HEADLINE> Blast Kills Three in Philippine Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Three people were killed and an
undetermined number of others injured this evening by a grenade
explosion in a crowded Catholic church in the Philippine capital
area of Metro Manila, police said.
</P>
<P>
The three victim were initially seriously wounded when an
unidentified man threw two fragmentation grenades into a crowd of
prayers inside Baclaran Catholic Church in Pasay city, Metro
Manila at 8:45 p.m., said a policeman from the Baranaque Police
District.
</P>
<P>
They died later in hospital, said the policeman who asked to be
anonymous.
</P>
<P>
The blast was widely believed to be in retaliation for the
leading role played by the Catholic Church in the September 21
mass rally against changes to the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Actually, an explosive device had been found by police inside
the church after the church received a bomb threat just one day
before the rally.
</P>
<P>
In mid-September, two explosions occurred in the capital area,
killing six people and wounding 60 others. Later, a shadowy
military claimed responsibility for the bombings and threatened
more bombings if the opposition to charter change persisted.
</P>
<P>
Since then, a wave of bomb threats swept private and public
offices, including Catholic churches and even the Supreme Court,
in Metro Manila. But most of them were found to be hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, Philippine President Fidel Ramos can
only serve single six-year term, and must step down in June 1998.
But his supporters have been pushing hard for constitutional
changes to remove the term limit for the president.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who has been accused by his critics of being behind the
drive to amend the charter, made it clear that he would not seek
another term, in a statement issued just several hours before the
September 21 rally.
</P>
<P>
The anti-charter change rally was led by Manila Archbishop
Jaime Cardinal Sin and former president Corazon Aquino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
