<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Seek Comprehensive and Just Peace: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat said today that the Palestinians are seeking comprehensive,
just and lasting peace along all the Arab tracks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to newsmen following his meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak in Egyptian port city of Alexandria,
Arafat said that he discussed with Mubarak the current
circumstances, challenges and difficulties facing the Arab nation,
particularly the Palestinian people, as a result of Israel's
failure to fulfill the agreements already approved by the
concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
According to the Middle East News Agency, Arafat criticized
Israel's attempts to evade its obligations regarding the release
of detainees as well as the full and honest implementation of the
agreement of Israeli troop withdrawal and redeployment in the
Palestinian territories. He also denounced Israeli designs to
Judaize Jerusalem and to confiscate Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also pointed out that Israel was delaying the opening of
the Gaza airport, refusing to permit the construction of the Gaza
harbor, obstructing the opening of the safe passage between the
West Bank and Gaza and failing to honor the dues which already
reached 34 cases.
</P>
<P>
On the outcome of the current New York tripartite meeting
between U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levi and the Secretary General of the
Executive Committee of the Palestine Liberation Organization
Mahmoud Abbas (alias Abu Mazen), Arafat said "we have to wait and
see."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian President Arafat left Alexandria this afternoon
after a brief stay of a few hours in the city.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had already visited Tunisia, Algeria and Morocco
before arriving in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
