<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cultural Show Staged in HK to Mark National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A cultural show staged today
at Hong Kong Coliseum to mark the National Day of China climaxed
when Singing the Motherland was being chorused by over 1,000
singers.
</P>
<P>
The banner reading Long Live the Motherland was seen high on
the stage when the chorus was echoed in the famous performing
venue.
</P>
<P>
The performance is one of some 130 commemorations throughout
Hong Kong to celebrate the 48th anniversary of the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Association of Compatriots in Hong Kong for
Celebration of the National Day, the show featured songs and
dances, cross-talk and acrobatics, with performers, totaling
1,500, coming from Hong Kong and China's interior areas.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the show, 60 white-uniformed members from
the Hong Kong Police Band played the National Anthem, while a huge
five-star red flag was raised on the backdrop of the stage.
</P>
<P>
An amateur troupe from the People's Liberation Army's Hong Kong
Garrison made their debut in the evening, with their song and
dance "Being A Soldier in Hong Kong" greeted by thundering
clappings.
</P>
<P>
Other programs include folk songs of China's minorities, pop
songs, ballet, modern dance as well as breath-taking acrobatics by
a group of children aged between 10 and 15 from China's interior.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, a line-up of senior government
officials and a host of local prestigious figures were among
thousands of audience at the two-hour show.
</P>
<P>
Henry Fok Ying-tung, vice chairman of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference, addressed the show on behalf of
the association. "We are so proud to brace the first National Day
after Hong Kong's reunification with the motherland," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon of the day, recreation and sports carnivals
were held in Victoria Park on Hong Kong Island and Sha Tin Sports
Ground, "the New Territories".
</P>
<P>
The carnival in Victoria Park, organized by the Provisional
Urban Council, featured various sports and games, including
traditional Chinese fun games like bowl-balancing and stilts. A
stage show produced by a local radio featuring popular singers
attracted a lot of fans.
</P>
<P>
At Sha Tin Sports Ground, some 600 students joined hands in
forming a giant map of China about the size of a soccer pitch. The
map, which contains heart-shaped wooden blocks with small balloons
and decorations on top, may help the youngsters get a better idea
of the shape of their motherland and the location of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The celebration, organized by the Provisional Regional Council,
also included Chinese traditional dances, gymnastic performances,
singing and colorful recreational and sports activities.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to China on July 1, Hong Kong people
now can enjoy two-day public holidays celebrating the National
Day, like their compatriots in China's interior areas.
</P>
<P>
It was the fireworks display over Victoria Harbor that drew a
perfect ending to the whole day's celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong people, especially kids, felt lucky enough to watch
the sixth fireworks display in the year of handover. On waterfront
across the harbor, families, lovers and friends were seen
everywhere crazy for the 23-minute extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
Police estimated that some 500,000 people feasted their eyes on
both sides of the harbor, while more watching from TV.
</P>
<P>
It was also the first time for them to enjoy fireworks on the
National Day. Traditionally, fireworks are only displayed on the
second day of the lunar new year.
</P>
<P>
The display was sponsored by the Federation of Hong Kong
Guangdong Community Organizations and fireworks were all made in
the Chinese interior.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
