<HEADLINE> Russia Accuses US of Interfering in Gas Deal with Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today accused the United States of trying to interfere with the
implementation of a natural gas deal signed between Iran and two
companies in France and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told reporters that both Russia and France are
independent states and whether they should or should not sign a
contract with somebody else was no business of other countries.
</P>
<P>
The French oil company Total on Sunday announced a two billion
U.S. dollar contract for exploration in Iran's South pars offshore
gas field along with its Russian partner, Russian Natural Gas
Monopoly (the GAZPROM).
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. called the contract a violation of its
Iran-Libya sanctions act, also called the D'Amato Act, and
threatened to impose sanctions upon Iran and the two companies.
</P>
<P>
The act bans all companies throughout the world from investing
more than 40 million dollars in the oil and hydrocarbon sector of
Iran and Libya, which Washington has accused of backing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin noted that Russia would not give up the contract under
pressure imposed by the U.S. He also expressed thanks to his
French counterpart, Jacques Chirac, who held the same view.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Roundup:  Thai Cabinet Scraps Hopewell Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is the first major infrastructure setback for Thailand since
the de facto devaluation of the baht on July 2.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six years of construction, progress on the
project, the Bangkok elevated road and train system, has been
slow, with only about 14 percent of the work done so far.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Hopewell (Thailand), a subsidiary of Hong
Kong-based Hopewell Holdings, and the Thai side have often openly
blamed each other for delays and lack of fund.
</P>
<P>
The multi-deck mass transit system, planned to complete within
eight years, was plagued by contractual disputes and technical
problems, including disagreements on the extension of the
concession period, payment of concession fee, connection with
expressways and fare structures.
</P>
<P>
Anusak Intharapuvasa, Hopewell (Thailand) vice chairman, said
his firm had liquidity problems because the Thai government's
decision to float the currency, which reduced the project's
expected return by 40 percent and prompted financial institutions
to suspend their plans to fund the project.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the project, estimated at 80 billion baht (3
billion U.S. dollars) at the time when the contract was signed,
would now exceed 4 billion U.S. dollars, as a result of the
depreciation of the Thai currency and economic slump.
</P>
<P>
Some academic sources said that the contract was signed even
before feasibility studies were completed.
</P>
<P>
The project consists of elevated trains, elevated tollways,
frontage roads and property development along its routes, most of
the routes were to run above the railway tracks in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The contract, signed on November 9, 1990, awarded Hopewell a
30-year concession plus eight years of construction. Hopewell was
given the right to develop 100 hectares of land commercially along
the routes and in some residential areas.
</P>
<P>
However, the current slump in the property sector and overall
economic downturn put the project in trouble.
</P>
<P>
Now Hopewell has the right to seek compensation for the 12
billion baht (333 million dollars) it has invested in the project,
while the Thai government also has a right for compensation for
the delay.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government will now inform Hopewell of its decision
and explain its reasons. If Hopewell does not accept the Thai
positions, the dispute must be submitted for arbitration, if
arbitration cannot settle the dispute, the two sides will have to
seek a court ruling, a process which could take as long as 10
years to complete.
</P>
<P>
Without the multi-deck project, the 13th Asian Games would not
be affected, because the construction of an alternative tollway
and a Bangkok outer ring road are under way, according to
Transport and Communications Minister Suwat Liptapallop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
