<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Construction Spending Declines in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Construction spending in the
U.S. declined by 0.3 percent in August, the third drop in the past
four months, U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the spending dropped to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 601.8 billion dollars in the month after a
1.6 percent increase to a record high in July.
</P>
<P>
The July's figure, which had previously been reported as a 0.5
percent gain, was revised upwards in the report.
</P>
<P>
The weakness of U.S. construction spending in August was led by
a 1 percent drop in government construction to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 137.6 billion dollars. There were
downturns of spending on schools, highways and streets and water
supply facilities.
</P>
<P>
Residential construction rose by 0.2 percent to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 260 billion dollars. But single-family
construction slipped 0.1 percent while apartment building and
remodeling projects increased.
</P>
<P>
Non-residential commercial construction fell 0.8 percent to an
annual rate of 163.9 billion dollars. Gains in hotels, private
schools and hospitals were more than offset by drops in
construction of factories, offices and retail stores. 
</P>
</TEXT>
