<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Congress to Pass Resolution for the </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today urged the legislators to pass a congressional resolution to
ensure the speedy return of former President Ferdinand Marcos'
assets in Swiss banks to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
During the 77th meeting of the Legislative-Executive
Development Advisory Council, Ramos reiterated the government
objective to get the Marcos wealth transferred from the Swiss
banks to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
He later stressed at his weekly press briefing that the
government has always been supportive of the claims of the 10,000
victims of human rights abuses during the Marcos time that they
should get compensation from Marcos' assets.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also laughed off as sheer fantasy the claim that there
are 1,241 tons of Marcos' gold deposited in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
"I was told that if all of the gold extracted from all of the
mines in the world over the last 25 years were put together in one
place, they wouldn't amount to 1,240 tons. Now, in my own
estimation what is 1,241 tons? That is more than 600 six-by-six
trucks loaded with gold of two tons each," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new controversy of Marcos' gold has resurfaced following
the allegation by American lawyer Swift who is a counsel for the
victims of human rights abuses. Swift said that there are 1,241
tons of gold owned by Marcos deposited in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
Swift also said a "memorandum of account" owned by Ramos
showed a secret deal on the Marcos wealth deposited in Swiss
banks.
</P>
<P>
Ramos Tuesday vehemently dismissed claims by Swift that he has
transferred some of the fabled Marcos gold to a bank account in
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Ramos denied he has a bank deposit in Switzerland. He admitted
he had an American dollar account "many years ago which I closed
even before I became President on June 30, 1992."  
</P>
</TEXT>
