<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Decide on UN Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Now that Africa's proposal to
secure two seats with a veto power on the U.N. Security Council
has been agreed on, it is now up to the continent to decide on
the countries to represent it, a zimbabwean official said today.
</P>
<P>
Briefing journalists at the end of President Robert Mugabe's
visit to the 52nd UN general assembly in New York, Foreign
Minister Stan Mudenge said although U.S. President Bill Clinton
agreed to changes in the UN Security Council, he felt it was the
responsibility of the continent to come up with their choices.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge said the two seats for Africa were in line with the
geographical representation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
''The U.N. reforms must now reflect the new economic order and
changes and not seek to maintain the status quo of the second
World War era,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge said the Organization of African Unity also welcome
the proposed U.N. reforms spelt out by U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan, but added that U.N. reforms for Africa would be
negotiated by African member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
