<HEADLINE> Shell Canada to Invest Heavily in Oilsands Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Shell Canada Ltd. has unveiled
plans for the development of a 1.3 billion U.S. dollar bitumen
upgrader at its refinery near Edmonton, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
The upgrader will only be built if the Calgary-based company
receives green light to develop a new 720 million dollar oilsands
mine and extraction plant in the province, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Bitumen is the tar-like substance that is recovered from the
oilsands.
</P>
<P>
It would be moved by a proposed pipeline to the Edmonton
upgrader, the third and final piece of the company's huge
integrated oilsands development.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed integrated oilsands development would more than
double the size of Shell Canada's current oil-and-gas business,"
the company said.
</P>
<P>
The company currently produces 90,000 barrels a day of
conventional oil and 730 million cubic feet a day of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Shell is one of the largest integrated petroleum companies in
Canada, with a total annual revenues of 3.7 billion dollars and
assets of more than 3.6 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
