<HEADLINE> People across China Celebrate National Day (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A theatrical show held in Urumqi, capital city of the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, was well-received with laughter and
applause. Troupes of farmers and herdsmen from nine ethnic groups,
including Uighur, Hui and Kazak ethnic groups, spent nine months
rehearsing the show.
</P>
<P>
In Kunming, capital city of southwest China's Yunnan province,
orchestral performances and other shows were also held to
celebrate the festival.
</P>
<P>
In Lhasa, capital city of the Tibet Autonomous Region, flags
are soaring over government buildings, and marketplaces are filled
with people buying goods. The city's residents, who are fond of
spending holidays in the open air, put up tents on the outskirts
of Lhasa, and sang and danced in the autumn sunshine.
</P>
<P>
Museums in the port city of Tianjin, north China, hosted
exhibitions to highlight the country's progress over the past
years.
</P>
<P>
Some cities celebrated the day by demonstrating their
achievements in economic development. Nanjing of Jiangsu province
has seen sharply increased foreign investments in this east China
city, and a number of state-owned enterprises in northeast
provinces are reported to have been revived.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output in northeast China's Liaoning province
increased by 9.2 percent in the first eight months of this year to
reach 137.1 billion yuan (16.5 billion US dollars) over the same
period of last year. And more foreign investments have been
pouring into the province.
</P>
<P>
In a small village near Guiyang, capital of southwest China's
Guizhou province, villagers from the Miao ethnic minority dressed
in their traditional festival costumes and danced into new
houses. The village was affected by heavy flooding last year, but
new houses have been built with the help of local government
funding.
</P>
</TEXT>
