<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Falls to New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso today fell
sharply, with its exchange rate against the U.S. dollar breaching
the so-called psychological level of 35 pesos at the local
currency market.
</P>
<P>
The local currency fell to as low as 35.61 pesos to the dollar
at the early trading in the Philippine Dealing System (PDS), the
country's computerized currency exchange system.
</P>
<P>
On the average, the peso was trading at 34.926 pesos to the
dollar at the PDS, 1.8 percent lower than Wednesday's 34.295
pesos.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the sharp depreciation of the peso to rising
demand for the dollar from investors who are losing confidence in
the peso and other Southeast Asian currencies and unloading them.
</P>
<P>
Currency experts said as long as other Southeast Asian
currencies fail to recover, it will be hard for the peso to
rebound.
</P>
<P>
The peso has already depreciated more than 31 percent since it
was allowed to float on July 11 in the face of fierce speculative
attacks against the currency.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank today refrained from actively
intervening in the local currency market under the policy of
preserving its limited foreign reserves of about 10.6 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the central bank raised its offer rate for the dollar to
35.70 pesos from 34.96 pesos for Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
