<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes Shut Down of Bosnia Transmitters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
expressed its endorsement to the action by NATO-led Salvation
Forces (SFOR) to shut down four television and radio transmitters
in the Republic Srpska, Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR troops raided and closed the transmitter stations
early today as it is alleged that the Bosnian Serb transmitters
have been used by those people loyal to former Bosnian Serb leader
Radovan Karadzic to denounce NATO and the Bosnian Peace Accords.
</P>
<P>
The British Foreign Office said in a statement issued this
afternoon that the London government "welcomes this morning's
decisive action by SFOR troops against four radio and TV
transmitters in Republic Srpska."
</P>
<P>
"Contact Group foreign ministers last week reaffirmed the right
of the (Bosnia) High Representative (Carlos Westendorp) to curtail
or suspend any media network or program whose output is in
persistent and blatant contravention of the (Bosnia) Peace
Agreement," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"We therefore fully support Carlos Westendorp's decision to
request military action against stations which undermine Dayton
(Agreement) not least by expressing support to Karadzic," it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
