<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Nepali Government Officials Tender Resignations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Six ministers and state
ministers tendered their resignations to Nepali Prime Minister
Lokendra Bahadur Chand Wednesday just one day before the Lower
House is to debate on the no-confidence motion against the
government tabled by the main opposition Nepali Congress (NC).
</P>
<P>
Among the six ministers are Finance Minister Rabindra Nath
Sharma, Commerce Minister Sarbendra Nath Shukla and Minister for
Land Reforms and Management Buddhiman Tamang, all of them come
from Chand's own National Democratic Party (RPP), an informed
source said.
</P>
<P>
But Prime Minister Chand will not accept these resignations at
this crucial moment, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Since the NC registered the no-confidence motion against the
present three-party government on September 22, a new round of
political drama has been unfolding in this Himalayan country.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the motion was registered in the Parliament
Secretariat, Prime Minister Chand effected a sixth change to his
cabinet since taking office in March, inducting three independents
as ministers and changing some portfolios.
</P>
<P>
But the next day, Gajendra Narayan Singh, who was transferred
from minister for supplies to minister without portfolio,
resigned.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on Singh's resignation, the Nepal Sadbhavana
(goodwill) Party, a coalition partner, accused Prime Minister
Chand of turning a blind eye to the problems of the Terai people
and of hurting the party's feelings by stripping its only minister
of his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Then on September 30, Minister of Supplies Moti Prasad Pahadi
who at first declined to take oath of office also resigned barely
four days after taking office.
</P>
<P>
The Lower House is set to debate on the no-confidence motion
from October 2 to 4 and vote on it on October 5 or 6.
</P>
<P>
While a total of 86 MPs from the NC had signed the
no-confidence motion, a simple majority of 103 votes is needed to
pass the motion in the 205-seat Lower House.
</P>
<P>
RPP President Surya Bahadur Thapa, Chand's arch rival, has not
made known his stand on the motion until now.
</P>
<P>
The RPP, which has 20 seats in the Lower House, is divided into
Thapa faction and Chand faction.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist-Leninist,
CPN-UML), has asked all its 89 MPs to vote against the
no-confidence motion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
