<HEADLINE> Fight Against Regional Crime Needed Coop: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- There is need for increased
regional and international cooperation if governments are to
combat crime successfully, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said today.
</P>
<P>
Opening the Interpol Sub-Regional Bureau for Southern Africa
here, Mugabe said, "if we demonstrate solidarity in our resolute
fight against crimes without the impediment of territorial
barriers, would-be criminals will become acutely aware that the
police organization of the world is collectively ranged against
them and that no country will provide refuge to fugitives."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said by providing premises for the sub-regional office,
the Zimbabwean government had shown commitment to the fight
against crime.
</P>
<P>
He urged other countries to contribute toward meeting the
costs of running the office.
</P>
<P>
The bureau is a regional facility whose major purpose is to
enable southern African countries to formulate and coordinate
joint strategies for the control and combat of cross border
crime.
</P>
<P>
"It is, therefore, imperative that member countries view it as
such in order to derive maximum benefit from its programs and
activities," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe commended the signing earlier of an agreement on
cooperation by member countries of the Southern African Regional
Cooperation Police Chiefs Organization (SARPCCO), saying this
would complement interpol's efforts in fighting crime in the
region.
</P>
<P>
However, Mugabe said to sustain these regional initiatives, it
was important that effective training programs were developed to
ensure that police in the region did not lag behind in the
international standards of investigating, detecting and
preventing crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
