<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Asks UN to Reexamine Cambodia's Seat Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian leader Hun Sen
is threatening to limit the United Nations' role in the scheduled
election of his country next May if the Organization does not give
his government Cambodia's seat in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen met with U.S. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday
evening to mainly discuss the issue of Cambodia's seat in the
world body.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodia's seat was declared vacant last month after the
United Nations tried but failed to preserve it for Prince Norodom
Ranariddh, the first Prime Minister of Cambodia, who was ousted in
July.
</P>
<P>
"It is the seat that belong to us and we have the right to
occupy it," Hun Sen told reporters after the meeting with the U.N.
head.
</P>
<P>
"If the issue of the seat of Cambodia cannot be resolved, we
will look into the matter" of the U.N. role in the elections, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen expressed hope that the members of the U.N. credentials
committee will re-examine their positions.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday night,Annan also met with Ranariddh in an effort to
persuade the two rivals of Cambodia to negotiate a peaceful
solution to the conflict and hold the election freely and fairly.
</P>
<P>
But the two Cambodians showed no sign of reconciliation. Hun
Sen said that during his stay in New York he had no reason to meet
Ranariddh as the latter had suggested earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen added that Ranariddh, who won the 1993 U.N.-supervised
election, was welcome to go back to Cambodia. But he refused to
guarantee Ranariddh's immunity from criminal charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Big Troop Reduction of SFOR in Bosnia: NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAASTRICHT, Netherlands, October 1 (Xinhua) -- NATO defense
ministers today agreed that there will be no significant troop
reduction of the multinational SFOR force in Bosnia in the run-up
to next June.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers were overwhelmed with the feeling that
SFOR should stay in Bosnia even after the local municipal
elections, not as otherwise required by the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
No minister, according to sources close to the annual informal
meeting, called for large reduction of troops between now and next
June when the SFOR mandate comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
It is because NATO credibility is too tied up to Bosnia to
afford a slip over the peacemaking mission. If the mission in
Bosnia should fail, it would be too difficult for the enlarging
military alliance to carry out future operations, the sources said
after the ministerial discussion.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers also agreed that what SFOR could not
achieve now with 36,000 troops cannot be achieved in the future
with less troops.
</P>
<P>
"The more we can do now, the easier the situation will be next
year," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A post-SFOR force cannot afford to be a reduced duplicate of
the present SFOR, the sources said. It has to be completely
redefined and constructed for a completely new mission with
different structure, mandate and relationship.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana told a press briefing that
the ministers had agreed NATO has to continue with the same
robustness and even-handedness in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief added that the SFOR mission will only terminate
at a time when a security framework has been set up in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht informal meeting gave NATO policy planners a
chance to compare notes on political views. They reached
consensus that SFOR has to remain in Bosnia for the coming
parliamentary elections slated for October 23.
</P>
<P>
NATO is expecting the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe to call upon its troops to help secure the elections
just as they did in the September 13-14 Bosnian municipal
elections.
</P>
<P>
A few defense ministers, however, said that SFOR should be able
to shed some of its troops without decisively reducing the
strength of the multinational force.
</P>
<P>
The three options of no reduction, small reduction and large
reduction will remain on table for the scheduled November and
December meetings of NATO defense ministers who prefer to see an
overall plan for not simply reducing the number of troops but
rather a plan for reconfiguring the troops to remain in Bosnia as
an effective deterrance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
