<HEADLINE> Cases of Cancer Rise Sharply in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Cases of cancer in Britain have
increased sharply over a 12-year period, with the figures for
women up 20 percent and for men 10 percent higher, according to an
annual medical report of the nation today.
</P>
<P>
Chief medical officer Kenneth Calman said in the report that as
a result of an increase in the number of women smokers, lung
cancer had overtaken breast cancer as the main cause of cancer
deaths among women in many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The report said that malignant melanoma, skin cancer had shown
the biggest single increase among cancers while prostate cancer
had increased by about 40 percent since 1979.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that prostate cancer could take over from
colorectal cancer as the second most common cancer in men if the
current trends continued.
</P>
<P>
However, death rates from heart disease and stroke were falling
and infant mortality reached its lowest ever rate last year, six
deaths per 1,000 live births. Life expectancy has increased to
79.5 years for women and 74.3 percent for men.  
</P>
</TEXT>
