<HEADLINE> Vietnam Calls on to Strengthen Development Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- In a world of
ever-deepened interindependence and under the impact of
globalization trends, the need for development cooperation was
becoming increasing strong, Vu Khoan, Deputy Minister for Foreign
Affairs of the Socialist Republic of Vietnam, stressed here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the fifty-second session of the General Assembly,
the deputy foreign minister said nations were facing unprecedented
opportunities for expanding market, engaging more
partners,intensifying investment and technology transfers in order
to attain a higher growth.
</P>
<P>
Vu said that there was the process of liberalization which had
made competition extremely acute, and in that competition the
advantages did not go to countries which were still at a low level
of economic development.
</P>
<P>
He said that the gap between the rich and the poor countries
was widening, thus causing great losses to developing nations. The
ratio of GDP per capita between the rich and the poor had gone up
to 61/1 in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Vu stressed that it was necessary to reverse the trend of
decreasing of the Official Development Aid both bilaterally and
multilaterally, at the time when developing countries badly needed
capital for infrastructure, construction, human resource
development, life-quality improvement, poverty alleviation,
eco-system and environment protection and so forth to address the
global issues facing every country, developed as well as
developing.
</P>
<P>
The deputy foreign minister said his country was looking
forward to stronger technology transfers as the outstanding and
rapid scientific and technological progress were posing a danger
of developing countries being left further behind.
</P>
<P>
Vu said it was high time to completely do away with the
obsolete ways of thinking and acting of the past, namely the
imposition of inequitable terms of economic and trade relations,
sanctions and embargoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
