<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mogadishu's Water System to Be Rehabilitated in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 1 (Xinhua) -- In just six months' time,
water will run again into the Somali capital Mogadishu, a German
aid agency announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The agency, German Diakonie Bread for the World (DBG), said
with funds from the German government, the main engines of the 32
water wells in Afgoie, about 18 km South of the capital, will be
repaired so as to supply clean water to the capital at low cost.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference today, the director of DBG,
Dietrich Frenkel, said that the spare parts will reach Mogadishu
within a month and once the repairs are done, the flow of water
will start.
</P>
<P>
Frenkel said his agency will also finance the repair works and
the building of the infrastructure of the distribution points.
</P>
<P>
The water project which will cost more than 0.5 million U.S.
Dollars has been Welcomed and supported by Mogadishu's main
political sides, according to Mr Frenkel, who said that "they
guaranteed the security and pledged not to impose taxes on the
transactions of the water project."
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu's water system will be privatized for the first time
and will become self sustaining project in six weeks time after
it starts running. "The water wells and their distribution system
will be run by Somalis who are independent from us and the
political factions," said Mr Frenkel.
</P>
<P>
The Afgoie water wells which were built also by a German
agency. Saarberg Interplan in 1982 remains one of the few
national assets that survived the destruction of the civil war
and subsequent widespread looting.
</P>
<P>
Four of the 12 heavy duty engines are to be repaired by DBG so
that two can operate alternatively at a time.
</P>
<P>
DBG has commended a group of Somalis who protected the well
fields throughout the civil war. Frenkel said, "I couldn't
believe my eyes when I saw some of the engines were even brand
new, still wrapped in their cartons."
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu's water system has been out of order since the
departure of the United Nations peace keepers from Somalia in
early March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Many of the pipe line installations of the city were also dug
out by looters. So the task of restoring Mogadishu's water system
will delight the people of the capital who have been drinking
unsafe water from unhygienic shallow wells. 
</P>
</TEXT>
