<HEADLINE> Southern African Ministers Sign Pact on Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 1 (xinhua) -- Southern African ministers
responsible for police matters today signed an agreement covering
cooperation and mutual assistance in combating crimes.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said in a communique issued here after the
signing ceremony that the accord was designed to lay a sound
basis and legal framework for regional police cooperation in
fighting cross border crime in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement will immeasurably strengthen the efforts of the
southern African regional cooperation police chiefs organization
and also the function of the Interpol Southern Africa Bureau in
developing effective crime combating strategies," the ministers
said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers from Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe signed the pact which now awaits
ratification.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, police officials may enter into any member
country to investigate suspected criminals or seize any exhibits
relating to offenses committed in their countries.
</P>
<P>
Police officers could also enter other countries to trace and
question witnesses in connection with any such offenses.
</P>
<P>
The right of entry would, however, be subject to the municipal
laws of the country visited and approval from officials in charge
of a central office which transmits and receives requests for the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Police in the hosting country would provide assistance to
their visiting counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Areas of specific cooperation under the agreement are the
exchange of crime related information and technical expertise on
a regular basis, and the planning, coordination and execution of
joint operations including under-cover operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
