<HEADLINE> NATO, Russia Not to Itemize Military Cooperation Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAASTRICHT, Netherlands, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The North
Atlantic Treaty Organization and Russia today failed to come out
with a detailed plan for their pronounced military-to-military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the first meeting between the NATO chief and the
new Russian defense minister, neither side could categorize what
their cooperation plans contain.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, however, described as
very good his meeting with Igor Sergeyev, the former commander of
the strategic missile force of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
He said that Sergeyev had planned to travel to the NATO
headquarters in Brussels later this month to further change ideas
as how to materialize the military-to-military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Russian defense minister told a joint press briefing with
Solana that his meeting with Solana and NATO defense ministers,
though not official, was very important in that it allowed him to
express Russia's general approach to the construction of
military-to-military cooperation within the established framework,
defined by the NATO-Russia Founding Act signed in May in Paris
during the NATO and Russia summit.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev also expressed at the informal meeting of NATO defense
ministers his country's readiness to exercise specific activities
on a permanent basis in the peacemaking mission in Bosnia and in
the construction of a new security framework in Europe as well as
Russian participation in it.
</P>
<P>
Russia, that blamed NATO for not consulting it before capturing
several pro-Radovan Karadzic radio and television transmitters in
Bosnia earlier this month, took part earlier today in another
NATO-led SFOR maneuver in which four pro-Pale transmitters were
captured and were planned to be handed to the Serbs in support of
the Republika Srpska president in Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR action, executed by some 400 troops with the Russians
blocking roads to prevent local unrest, took place without
incident, according to NATO sources.
</P>
<P>
Initial NATO-Russia military-to-military cooperation may have
to start with the arrival of a Russian permanent representative at
the NATO headquarters where each NATO member state is represented
permanently.
</P>
<P>
The Russian defense minister announced today that his country's
representative will arrive in NATO between October and November.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether he trusted the 16-nation alliance as a new
security partner, Sergeyev said that he trusted the implementation
of the agreements reached between the two parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
