<HEADLINE> Team of Researchers Discovers Two Hominid Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 1 (xinhua) -- A team of researchers at
the Konso site in Ethiopia have discovered two coexisting hominid
species known as homo erectus and Australopithecus Boisei between
1993 and 1997, the Ethiopian News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Konso-Gardula research area, about 500 kilometers south of
Addis Ababa, is one of the paleoanthropological sites discovered
by a survey team led by Ethiopian professionals in the late 1980s
and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The Konso paleoanthropological site is the third site in the
world following Olduvai Gorge, Tanzania, and Lake Turkana, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The report said, the Australopithecus Boisei found in 1993 at
Konso site was not known north of the Omo River, adding that homo
erectus has been found in different parts of Ethiopia including
the Middle Awash, Melka Konture and the Omo Basin.
</P>
<P>
All discovered at Konso are diverse stone tools which derive
from a multitude of time horizons spanning the 1.9 to 1.4 million
years.
</P>
<P>
The world's oldest well-dated assemblages are included in
these finds, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers' Strike Tightens Kenyan Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Kenyan teachers
started a nationwide pay strike today, ignoring the government's
repeated warning and thus simmering the political atmosphere
ahead of general elections set for later this year.
</P>
<P>
In many schools in Nairobi, Kerugoya, Nakuru, Yatta and other
areas, teachers reportedly downed their tools by either failing
to turn up in schools, or staging a sit-in in classrooms, or
taking to the street for protests, said local sources today.
</P>
<P>
In a majority of secondary schools around the country,
teaching is going on as usual. But "in primary schools most
teachers were not able to continue with their normal duties,"
according to a governmental statement issued today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement warned that "the teachers who...
participate in the illegal strike will be committing an unlawful
act and shall be guilty of an offence."
</P>
<P>
The 24,000-member Kenya National Union of Teachers (KNUT),
which sponsored the stoppage, vowed last night that the strike
will go on until the government meets the teachers' 200-percent
pay hike demand.
</P>
<P>
The strike is widely believed to hurt the ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) in the coming elections as teachers, among
the lowest paid professionals in Kenya, carry considerable
political influences especially in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
It is the latest in a series of illegal rallies, protests,
demonstrations and turmoil having emerged since May in the
eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
The government argued that the KNUT demand is unacceptable
because it means some 56 percent of governmental expenditure, or
nearly 90 billion Shillings (1.47 billion U.S. Dollars), has to
be used on salaries for teachers alone.
</P>
<P>
The government said that it is not in a position to adequately
remunerate public employees, including teachers, due to economic
pressures and financial constraints following the International
Monetary Fund cut a key loan to Kenya on July 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
