<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Canada Raises Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Canada raised
interest rate today by 25 basis points in a bid to slow down the
rapid-growing economy.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's bank rate and its operating band for the
overnight rate was raised by 0.25 percentage point to 3.75 percent
and to 3.25 -3.75 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time this year that the Bank of Canada
increased its interest rates. Its last rate hike came on June 26.
</P>
<P>
"In recent months there has been growing evidence that the
Canadian economy is expanding rapidly and absorbing unused
capacity," the bank said today in a brief statement.
</P>
<P>
"Indicators of aggregate demand, output, and money supply
growth have all been strong."
</P>
<P>
"Given the lags between monetary policy actions and their
effect on the economy, timely action to moderate the extent of
monetary stimulus will contribute to making the economic expansion
long lasting," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's move was followed quickly by Canada's major
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Bank of Canada was first off the mark with an
increase in the prime lending rate to 5.25 percent from 4.75
percent.
</P>
<P>
Its new rate was matched by all the other major banks.
</P>
<P>
The latest pre-emptive strike came amid speculations that the
central bank would act soon to cool down the red-hot economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada reported on Tuesday that the country's gross
domestic product (GDP) grew by 0.8 percent in July, doubling the
pace of growth forecasters had been expecting.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the economy has expanded at an annual rate
above three percent, almost twice the growth rate of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The strong GDP growth in July has prompted economists to revise
their growth forecasts for the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Paul Ferley, assistant chief economist at Bank of Montreal,
predicted a growth rate of 4.4-5 percent for the third quarter, up
from a previous forecast of 3.75-4.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
