<HEADLINE> Botswana's Economy Continues to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Botswana's economy
continued to grow with its foreign reserves going up and
inflation coming down.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's foreign reserves stood at 19.4 billion Pula (about
5.4 billion U.S Dollars) by the end of May, up 21.9 percent
compared with the figure 12 months before, the South African
Press Association quoted the Bank of Botswana as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation in August this year was running at 8.5
percent, down from the 9.9 percent a year before.
</P>
<P>
Growth in GDP (Gross Domestic Product) is estimated to have
more than doubled in the 1995-96 period over 1994-95. In 1995-96,
the growth rate was provisionally 7 percent, while in 1994-95, it
was 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the year, the bank rate and the primary rate dropped to
12.5 percent and 14.0 percent respectively. 
</P>
