<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Urged to Respect and Care for Older </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of older people
from Addis Ababa gathered today at the National Lottery here in
celebration of International Day of Older Persons, calling for
giving due respect and providing care to older persons in
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth time that Ethiopians celebrated
International Day of Older Persons. There are more than 2.5
million people in Ethiopia who are 60 and above, 4.5 percent of
the population of 56 million in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Mengesha Hailemelekot, an official
from the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs, said it is the
responsibility of the government and the population at large to
support and take care of older persons who in their youth and
adulthood had contributed much for the benefit of their country
and its people.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "with population explosion, the development
of cities, the introduction of modern civilization and the widely
rampant social problems, our tradition of helping one another has
been deteriorating from time to time leaving several of our
elderly compatriots with no one to care for them."
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by the attendants at the meeting, demanded
for the establishment of a facility where the older persons could
keep themselves busy and be self-supportive and an association as
well as a national federation for the older persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
