<HEADLINE> Turkish Jets Bomb PKK Camps in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish warplanes today bombed
camps of the Kurdish rebels in a continuous military operation in
northern Iraq, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
were hit by the jets as they fled the area.
</P>
<P>
The report failed to give the number of the military planes
involved in today's air raid.
</P>
<P>
Turkish ground forces, backed by air and artillery fire,
captured a main PKK camp in Zap on Tuesday, and attacked
three other camps in the region.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the fighting is continuing in the regions of Kani,
Mazi, Ekmal Bervari, Meti, Carcel in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkish fighter-bombers carried out an air strike on 15 PKK
camps last Thursday in northern Iraq where more than 1,000 PKK
militants were reportedly gathering for infiltration into
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Around 15,000 Turkish troops, backed by 130 tanks, crossed
into northern Iraq early last week to strike the PKK rebels there
and some 130 PKK militants have been killed so far, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military said that the gathering of the PKK rebels
in northern Iraq posed a serious threat to Turkey's border
security, saying that such operations would continue as long as
the threat existed.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkish Foreign Ministry said earlier that the
ongoing military operation in northern Iraq is only "a routine
and limited action."
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops have frequently launched cross-border actions in
northern Iraq over the past two years, causing severe criticism
from neighboring countries and some international bodies.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old war against the
Turkish government for the establishment of an independent Kurdish
state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
More than 27,000 people, including soldiers, civilians and
rebels, were killed in the armed clashes between the Turkish
government troops and PKK rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
