<HEADLINE> Cuba Calls for Breaking U.S. Blockage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Cuba is calling for world
support in its continuous efforts in breaking up the blockage
imposed by the United States for the past three decades and more.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 52nd session of the U.N. General Assembly today,
Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina said the U.S. embargoes had
cost his country more than 60 billion U.S. dollars so far. He
called on the member states of the U.N. to stand up to fight
against "the imperial power who wants to subdue the world."
</P>
<P>
The economy of the country was distorted by the war conditions,
he said, and unmeasurable human, physical and psychological damage
sustain each new Cuban denunciation.
</P>
<P>
On top of all that, Cubans were deprived of free access to
medications that appeared in the market after 1979, including
third generation antibiotics and others to treat AIDS and cancer,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
The blockade has been cruelly and arrogantly reinforced in the
eyes of the world, according to the Cuban foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. legislation also enacted some acts as a new escalation
of that blockade, he said. Such measures already harass over 35
countries of the world, that is, 2.3 billion people accounting for
42 percent of the world population and a potential market of 790
billion U.S. dollars, apart from global damage, Robaina quoted
some figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
