<HEADLINE> US Frustrated Over French-Iranian Gas Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright has criticized France over a 2 billion dollar natural gas
deal with Iran, while admitting Washington has no leverage in
preventing Paris from doing so.
</P>
<P>
She complained in a Tuesday's speech to the Council on Foreign
Relations, a private group in New York, that U.S. friends and
allies had not heard Washington's warning that Iran is "supporting
terrorism and undermining the Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
But she said the United States lacked leverage in trying to
stop France investing in Iran as it has no aid program for France,
for example, that could be turned on or off depending on whether
Paris backed the U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
"It is, indeed, frustrating," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration on September 29 threatened to impose
sanctions on the Total Co., the French oil giant, and other
companies of Russia and Malaysia for their contracts with Iran
over the 2 billion dollar gas deal.
</P>
<P>
But France returned with scoff, saying the United States has no
right to impose its law beyond its border.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody accepts that the United States can pass a law on a
global scale," French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said Monday.
"American laws apply in the United States. They do not apply in
France."
</P>
<P>
It was said Undersecretary of State Suart Eizenstat is to go to
Paris to convey the U.S. opposition to the contract. Meanwhile,
the United States is negotiating with the European Union to try to
resolve trans-Atlantic differences over trade with Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
