<HEADLINE> UK Deputy PM Outlines New Vision for Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIGHTON, England, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Prime Minister
John Prescott today announced measures to boost investment in
Britain's railways, put the passenger first and ensure private
operators provide high quality services.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Labor Party's Conference, Prescott pledged
that central to his vision would be a new priority for the Rail
Franchising Director.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the longer term, the government will need to
legislate to put its objectives into practice. But today's
announcement marks a crucial first step towards a revitalized
industry, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government will set new objectives for the Franchising
Director to signal a real shift in railways policy -- putting
passengers first, according to Prescott.
</P>
<P>
He said that private sector operators will face tough
regulation to ensure they honor their commitment and justify the
massive amounts of public money being pumped into the rail
industry.
</P>
<P>
The government will also be looking to develop a constructive
partnership with them, encouraging investment and cooperation and
making sure companies like Railtrack pull their weight, Prescott
added.
</P>
<P>
It was announced that the Franchising Director's objectives
will:
</P>
<P>
-- Put further franchising on hold;
</P>
<P>
-- Establish a new "Rail investment" role for the Franchising
Director;
</P>
<P>
-- Make the Franchising Director more accountable; and
</P>
<P>
-- Safeguard passenger benefits.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, Prescott said, "The announcement is simply an
interim first step. If we want to achieve all our objectives for
rail, we will need radical reform." 
</P>
</TEXT>
