<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The African National
Congress (ANC), today welcomed the subpoenas served on former
president P. W. Botha and some of his cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
The subpoenas will compel them to appear before the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission on the role of the State Security
Council next month.
</P>
<P>
"The subpoenas served on members of the former State Security
Council is a welcome development towards the achievement of the
objective of national reconciliation and unity," a statement of
the ANC said.
</P>
<P>
Others subpoenaed include former defense minister Magnus
Malan, former law and order minister Darian Vlok and the
council's former secretary Pierre van der Westhuizen.
</P>
<P>
Former foreign minister Pik Botha and cabinet colleagues Roelf
Meyer and Leon Wessels accepted invitations to the council
hearing and were subsequently subpoenaed as a formality.
</P>
<P>
"The process of reconciliation requires answers about the
activities not only of the SSC (State Security Council), but also
all key structures falling immediately under it in the national
security management system and the national coordinating
mechanism," said the statement by ANC spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa.
</P>
<P>
"The State Security Council controlled a totalitarian national
network which reached into every part of the country, identifying
anti-apartheid activists, formulating a continuous national
security profile and making decisions on action at national and
local levels."
</P>
<P>
These decisions were then implemented by formal law
enforcement structures backed by legislation, or by other
structures acting covertly, Mamoepa said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the members served with subpoenas should provide
answers on how security and third force networks functioned, how
extensive they were, what has happened to the networks and what
capacity these networks have to destabilize our new democracy."
</P>
<P>
The ANC maintains that the activities of the networks both
at home and abroad, including cross border raids and various
forms of violence, could not have taken place without the
knowledge of key officials at the highest levels of the
intelligence and security services as well as the State
Security Council, the statement said. 
</P>
