<HEADLINE> British Sale of Weapons to Kuwait Flourishes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain sold more than 310
million U.S. dollars of military equipment to Kuwait in 1996,
accounting for one third of its total exports to the country in
the year, Kuwait News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
This figure was announced today by Mike Hurley, a first
secretary of the British embassy here at a press conference on the
occasion of a visit to Kuwait by a delegation of the British
Cambridge Chamber of Trade and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Hurley said Britain exported to Kuwait 580 million pounds
sterling (more than 940 million dollars) worth of goods last year,
or 77 percent of the trade volume between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said military equipment, amounting to one third of British
exports to Kuwait, was followed by oil machinery, car, household
appliances, foodstuff, clothes and textile among other goods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, head of the British chamber delegation Barry Dare
said that during his visit here he would discuss ways with local
businessmen, representatives of the private sectors and the
Kuwaiti Chamber of Trade and Industry to enhance trade relations
between the both sides.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is the third largest market for British goods in the
Gulf region and the fourth in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Britain is one of the Western allies that has signed military
cooperation agreements with Kuwait following the Gulf War in 1991
that liberated Kuwait from Iraqi occupation.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, Kuwait could buy from Britain the
military equipment it needs to help rebuild the armed forces
destroyed by Iraqi troops during the Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial figures show that Britain has sold to Kuwait more
than 2 billion dollars worth of weapons since the end of the Gulf
War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
