MAASTRICHT, Netherlands, October 2 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary
General Javier Solana today reaffirmed that enlargement costs will
be perfectly manageable and should not be magnified.
</P>
<P>
Solana made the remark after NATO defense ministers met their
counterparts from Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic, the
three invitees for joining the 16-nation military alliance in
April 1999.
</P>
<P>
Czech Defense Minister Miloslav Vyborny, Polish Defense
Minister Stanislaw Dobrzanski and Hungarian Defense Minister
Gyorgy Keleti briefed the informal meeting of NATO defense
ministers on their preparations for accession.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief expressed his satisfaction with the fact that
all three invitees had turned in on time the NATO defense
planning questionnaires concerning their respective military
hardware and software.
</P>
<P>
The questionnaires will be part of the NATO cost evaluation and
calculation to be completed by late November this year.
</P>
<P>
Judging by the briefings, according to NATO sources, Hungary
looked to be better prepared, whereas Poland was less ready.
</P>
<P>
Today's joint meeting, the first between NATO defense ministers
and their counterparts from the three invited countries, was hailed as a
dress rehearsal of the accession to be held one and a half year
from now.
</P>
<P>
However, Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic were warned
that getting the invitation at the NATO Madrid summit last July
does not mean that they were guaranteed to automatically become
full members after the elapsed time of 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Starting from next January, the parliaments of the 16 NATO
member states will start ratifying the accession process and the
Americans are likely to be the most difficult to persuade to
approve the enlargement, which was initiated primarily by the
urging of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic exposed 11 deficiencies in its defense
planning questionnaire, and accession to NATO enjoyed only
50-percent support in a recent poll in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Czechs promised to catch-up by increasing defense
expenditures to account for 0.3 percent of its gross domestic
product by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarians wanted to involve its neighboring countries in
the joint security mechanism. But they must first of all conduct
the scheduled referendum concerning the accession.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian parliamentarians, on an earlier move, postponed the
referendum, which had been slated for November 19.
</P>
<P>
The Polish defense minister said the recent elections affirmed
the maturity and stability of his country, and the new government
will support the integration into the Euro-Atlantic partnership.
</P>
<P>
But the Poles raised concerns on procurement of modern weapons.
</P>
<P>
NATO defense ministers pointed out that it is wrong to think
that enlargement is all about buying new weapons. It is much more,
one NATO source said.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers saw the willingness of the three invitees
to commit reasonable financial resources to the process of
accession as agreeable; they felt reassured that a larger NATO has
to be stronger.
</P>
<P>
Solana told a press conference after the meeting that
enlargement is the right direction for development and
described the meeting with the three invitees as fruitful and
important.
</P>
<P>
He said that Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic know what
they have to do to qualify for NATO membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
