<HEADLINE> Belarussian President's Denied Entry to Russian Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko today cancelled his visits to the Russian cities of
Lipetsk and Yaroslavl, scheduled for October 2-3, after Russia
refused his travel plan, the Interfax news service reported.
</P>
<P>
Head of Lukashenko's office, Mikhail Myashikovich, said that
Lukashenko had planned to fly to Lipetsk to open an exhibition of
Belarussian commodities.
</P>
<P>
He said the visit was cancelled because the Russian side did
not let Lukashenko's plane land at the airport of Lipetsk.
</P>
<P>
Leonid Scherbakov, head of the traffic-control department of
the Russian Federal Air Service, was quoted as saying that flight
plans for Lukashenko to Lipetsk and Yaroslavl had never been
registered in its daily planning logs.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin expressed surprise at
Lukashenko's visit to the two Russian cities without notifying
him, the report said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It doesn't happen here that the president of another
state comes to Russia without the knowledge of the Russian
president. Let him release (Pavel) Sheremet first," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sheremet is the head of the Minsk bureau of Russian Public
Television (ORT), who is now in custody in Belarus.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Russian Embassy in Minsk would neither confirm
nor deny reports that the Russian side had annulled the diplomatic
document permitting Lukashenko's plane to land in Lipetsk and
Yaroslavl.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko expressed regrets over the incident, saying he hoped
friendly relations between Belarus and Russia would develop
despite "the political games played by some kremlin circles."
</P>
</TEXT>
