<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Warns of Acute Health Situation in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) warned here today that health conditions in the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) is an increasingly serious
problem.
</P>
<P>
A WHO team that visited the DPRK on September 15-20 found that
many basic public health programs have been suspended or
drastically curtailed due to natural disasters and economic
problems in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The result is a decrease in immunization activities and an
increase in child malnutrition," WHO said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The team also found that the country's surveillance, prevention
and control systems do not function well enough to protect the
people from the threat of diseases such as tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
Because of a lack of tuberculosis control programs and
tuberculosis drugs, WHO estimated that the mortality of
tuberculosis cases could reach 50 percent in the DPRK, which
reports 10,000 tuberculosis cases per year.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of natural disasters that have hit the
country, power supplies have been severely curtailed, thus
immunization programs that depend on a reliable cold chain for the
delivery of effective vaccines have been suspended.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, available replacement vaccines cannot be distributed
due to a lack of fuel for transport.
</P>
<P>
Malnutrition among infants and children, including anaemia and
Vitamin A deficiency, is also a serious problem, said WHO.
</P>
<P>
Since there is an acute shortage of most ordinary drugs in the
DPRK hospitals and clinics, WHO, in cooperation with the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), Medecins san Frontieres and the
Red Cross, is planning to provide them with drugs and medical
supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
