<HEADLINE> 35 Killed by Land Mines in South Korea since 1992 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-five people have been killed
and 43 others wounded by land mines in South Korea since 1992, the
Defense Ministry said in a report to the National Assembly Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Based on the report submitted by the ministry, lawmaker Chung
Dong-young of the main opposition party claimed children were among
the 29 civilian victims, mostly in northern Kangwon Province near the
Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) separating the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
Chung claimed there is an intricate web of land mines near the
DMZ, some dispersed through about 160 acres, and whose precise
location remains unknown even to military authorities.
</P>
<P>
Mountainous Yanggu County in Kangwon Province is also a mined
area, and 55 people have suffered injuries or died after stepping
on explosive devices there, Chung added.
</P>
<P>
"There are more than 1 million land mines along the DMZ, most
of which remain armed and deadly," the lawmaker said. "We have to
raise public awareness by disclosing their location."
</P>
<P>
Mines were also unearthed and carried south of the civilian
control line by last year's floods and have yet to be recovered,
Chung said.
</P>
<P>
The lawmaker asked military authorities to take measures to
remove the mines in areas frequented by civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
