<HEADLINE> Experts: Falllout From Atomic Bomb Tests Raises Cancer Alarm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Some experts testified at a
Senate subcommittee hearing Wednesday that the public was not
informed in time of the cancer risks from radioactive fallout from
U.S. nuclear bomb tests 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The National Cancer Institute (NCI) Wednesday released
information from a study on radiation from atomic bomb tests
in the 1950s that predict an increase in thyroid cancer of 2
percent to 20 percent above normal.
</P>
<P>
The Senators and experts criticized the agency for failing to
offer useful information to millions of Americans who had been
exposed as children to fallout from 90 atmospheric bomb blasts at
the Nevada Test Site near Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
The NCI estimated that the 90 bomb tests put enough iodine-131
in the air to create health problems as far away as the East
Coast, and 10,000 to 75,000 Americans may develop thyroid cancer
in their lifetime because of the exposure.
</P>
<P>
At particular risk are those who were children living in "hot
spots" and who drank a great deal of milk during the test period,
because I-131 builds up in grazing cattle and is transmitted
readily through milk.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post reported today that thyroid cancer has been
increasing at about 0.9 percent per year in recent decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
