<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Major Inflation in China This Year: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Economic experts have ruled out
the possibility of any major inflation in China for the rest of
the year, according to a report in today's Shanghai Securities
News.
</P>
<P>
The experts noted that at present, the general supply and
demand in the Chinese market will have a stabilizing effect on
prices, with all major commodities' supply exceeding the market
demand.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country's agricultural sector has scored bumper
grain harvests for three years in a row, and urban residents'
buying mentality remains calm.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they said, even if there is a slight rebound in
commodity prices in the final months of 1997, the annual increase
of the consumer goods retail price index could be controled to around
two percent, and the residents' consumption price index would rise
by no more than 5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
