<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Intl Aid Agencies Close Offices in Kismayu, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The international aid agency
of World Concern said it has suspended its operations in the
Southern port town of Kismayu, 500 km South of Mogadishu,
effective as from September 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kismayu said the decision of World Concern was
prompted by the killing of two of its local staff members inside
their office on August 20 while carrying out their daily job.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the agency has characterized the
killing of its employees as an unjustifiable and unacceptable act
against the humanitarian activities they were undergoing in
Kismayu.
</P>
<P>
The deceased local aid workers belonging to the Marehan
sub-clan were murdered by Majerten militiamen during the height
of clan animosity between the two sub-clans over the control of
Kismayu.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities in Kismayu have failed to punish those
responsible for killing the two aid workers who were serving at
the out-door patient clinic run by World Concern in the town.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the VHF radio in the town indicate that World
Concern will also shut down its mother and child health care post
inside Kismayu. The agency was also treating hundreds of people
suffering from various mental disorders.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the office of the U. N. aid agency of UNICEF was
closed down early in the week for security related matters.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the closure of UNICEF's office in Kismayu took
place after a UNICEF chartered plane trying to land at the
airport of the town was fired upon by Somali gunmen.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft allegedly transporting medicine and other health
utensils had to return to Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The airport of Kismayu has been a troubled point where rival
militiamen exchange fire at the arrival of aircraft. Two people
were killed at the airport a few days ago when fighting erupted
on dispute over the narcotic leaves of khat transported to the
airport by a Cesna plane.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the two aid agencies offices in Kismayu is a
major setback to the already poor humanitarian situation in the
town especially when it is in bad need of more humanitarian
supplies of food and medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
