<HEADLINE> Lassa Fever Claims 47 Lives in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 2 (Xinhua)-- Lassa Fever has claimed 47
lives between March and September in the east of Sierra Leone, a
Clinical report said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, 300 patients were admitted to
hospitals between March and September and 47 of them died. The
highest number of admissions for one month was in March when 147
patients were brought into the Clinic in Panguma in the east and
22 of them later died.
</P>
<P>
Other deaths have gone unrecorded for lack of transportation,
he said.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with the Senior Nurse in Chrgem Balu
Sankoh, the towns of Tongo, Panguma and Kenema, all diamond
mining areas were the hardest hit by the disease.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the patients suffered from diarrhoea while
the rest had symptoms of vomiting, fever, sore-throat, low blood
pressure and chest pains.
</P>
<P>
The Medical Officer in charge of the Clinic, Amiru Cohteh told
Xinhua that the epidemic escalated last year.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the cause to poor sanitation, rats overcrowding
and poor diet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
