<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Areas, SEZs of China Seek Higher Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Governments and people in
China's coastal areas and Special Economic Zones (SEZ) are seeking
ways to make their economies grow more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao, a coastal city in east China's Shandong Peninsula, has
worked out plans to promote foreign trade, improve the local
service sector and attract more foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Yantai, another coastal city in the peninsula, has so far
restructured 1,133 local enterprises. It is now considering
deepening the ownership reform and speeding up the introduction of
the shareholding and joint stock-partnership systems.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou, a picturesque city known as the "paradise on earth" in
east China's Jiangsu Province, plans to revitalize the state-owned
economy by optimizing the use of state capital and reshuffling
local state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Suzhou City Government claimed that it would make every
effort to preserve and increase the value of state assets,
introduce competitiveness into enterprise operation and
employment, and set up a social security system that covers every
local citizen.
</P>
<P>
Ningbo, a port city in east China's Zhejiang Province, boasts
one of the country's four first-class deep-water harbors -- the
Beilun Harbor.
</P>
<P>
Last year the cargo handling capacity of the Ningbo port
reached over 76 million tons, ranking third in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We will seize the current golden opportunity to build the
Beilun Harbor into China's second largest international harbor
after Shanghai. By the year 2000, Beilun will have an annual cargo
handling capacity of over 100 million tons," said Ye Xinhu,
director of the Ningbo Port Administration.
</P>
<P>
The Pudong New Development Area in China's largest city
Shanghai has become one of the country's most rapidly developed
areas over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
"Pudong will make full use of the macro market structure it has
developed in past years to serve the reshuffle of assets and
multi-national operation of enterprises, especially large
state-owned enterprises and groups," said an official in charge of
the area's economic affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
