<HEADLINE> Australia Cannot Be Complacent About Asian Students: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- - Australia could not afford to
be complacent about its ability to continue attracting large
numbers of Asian students to study here, Education Minister Amanda
Vanstone warned today.
</P>
<P>
Australia would need to start looking at alternative markets in
order to maintain the current 2.1 billion US dollar a year
industry, Australia's fifth largest service export earner, or
about 3 percent of the country's total exports, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot be complacent ... and we must continue to strive to
maintain the highest standard of education and training in the
Asia Pacific region," she said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of the Australian International
Education Foundation's (AIEF) booklet to promote vocational
education overseas, the minister said Australia would start
looking at new overseas student markets.
</P>
<P>
Recent AIEF data has indicated a fall off in the number of new
overseas students for the first half of this year in the region.
</P>
<P>
The foundation warned that numbers could drop further next year
when the race debate sparked by independent MP Pauline Hanson
could impact on enrollments.
</P>
<P>
She said the continued flow of overseas students here would
help promote Australia as a friendly and tolerant nation.
</P>
<P>
Vanstone's comments follow the release earlier this week of a
study showing Malaysian students saw Australia as a racist and
unsafe country because of press reports about Pauline Hanson.
</P>
<P>
Hanson, who advocates a cut in intake of Asian immigration and
an end to foreign investment in Australia, has been widely seen as
a racist.
</P>
<P>
The minister has previously warned that Hanson was costing
Australia jobs every time she opened her mouth, while "damaging
our reputation among Asian students."  
</P>
</TEXT>
