<HEADLINE> Algerian President Rejects FIS Appeal for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Algiers, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Liamine Zeroual
has rejected an appeal by the outlawed Islamic Salvation Front (FIS)
to hold talks with Islamic groups, despite a unilateral truce
announced by the military wing of FIS, the Islamic Salvation Army (AIS).
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of the cabinet on Wednesday, Zeroual
described as "fantastic and unfounded rumors" reports that the
Algerian authorities had been holding secret talks with the FIS
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
In response to suggestions that clemency be given by the
government to the Islamists who have given up the armed struggle,
he said the case of FIS has definitely been closed.
</P>
<P>
Zeroual denied that differences exist among various state
institutions over whether a re-examination of the FIS case should
be made.
</P>
<P>
The FIS leaders in exile in Europe said the truce, announced by
AIS on September 24, became effective on Wednesday, but the
Algerian media today remained extremely prudent about its effect.
</P>
<P>
The truce announcement coincided with a brutal wave of
massacres of civilians around the capital Algiers over the past
few weeks, for which another radical Islamic group, the Armed
Islamic Group (GIA), has claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The AIS, which had been active in the west and the east of the
country but not around the capital, said that it decided to start
the truce after holding negotiations with unspecified Algerian
government organs.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, an FIS bulletin, El Ribat, said on Wednesday that the
truce was concluded between the AIS and the National People's Army
of Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The FIS demanded that the truce should be followed up by a
general amnesty, the lifting of the state of emergency, which has
been in force since 1992, and the holding of a national
reconciliation conference to be attended by all state
institutions, the FIS and other Algerian groups without exclusion.
</P>
<P>
The FIS and AIS said the truce does not make up a surrender to
the government, but is instead the first step toward a negotiated,
political solution to the six-year-old Algerian conflict.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 people have been killed in Algeria since 1992,
when the country was plunged into violence after the army canceled
an election result that could have brought Islamists to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
