<HEADLINE> Malaysia Outlines Carrot-And-Stick for Athletes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian officials and
athletes who breached the code of conduct would have to repay
expenses incurred in the South Asian Games in Jakarta, Olympic
Council of Malaysia (OCM) President Hamzah Abu Samah said.
</P>
<P>
"We will propose that those caught for indiscipline pay back
all expenses incurred... the time has come for severe actions be
taken against those black sheep," Hamzah was reported as saying by
Bernama news agency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Their associations would also be made answerable for their
indiscipline and may face punitive actions from the OCM, he said.
</P>
<P>
The OCM had to fork out about 1.5 million ringgit (500,000
U.S. dollars) to send its contingent of 530 athletes and 230
officials for the biennial SEA Games from October 11-19.
</P>
<P>
The OCM is an umbrella body which has to endorse athletes
participation in international multi-sports events, while the
government-based National Sports Council handles funding for
training and overseas stints.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah said beer company Carlsberg had pledged 1,000 ringgit
for each gold medal while the National Sports Council has promised
5,000 ringgit under its incentive program.
</P>
<P>
For athletics, an additional 1,000 ringgit is offered by the
Malaysian Amateur Athletics Association for a gold medal, a new
national record or a new SEA games record.
</P>
<P>
Officials are targetting 50 gold medals from the Games this
time mostly in martial arts and athletics, compared to 31 gold
medals in the 1995 SEA Games in Chiengmai, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
A total of 440 gold medals will be up for grabs in 34 events in
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah said the best Malaysian athlete of the day throughout
the Games would also be rewarded with 2,000 ringgit cash and a
medal, under an incentive scheme between OCM and John Hancock Life
Insurance since 1995.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the winner's association will receive 1,000
ringgit for their role in "training and developing future stars,"
Hamzah added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
