<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- France today approved of the move
by the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRCongo) to send observers to
the neighboring Congo Republic, while expressing regret over its
decision to re-call international investigators looking into the
massacres of Hutu refugees in the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"Sending observers will help put an end to the bombardment and
counter-bombardment (in Brazzaville); it will also serve to avoid
confrontations and violence, and hopefully help avoid the
escalation of tension," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman
Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Democratic Republic of Congo said
Wednesday it would send a group of observers to Brazzaville to
establish a "corridor" to keep Kinshasa safe and to investigate
the cases of firings across the Zaire (Congo) River into Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made during a visit to Kinshasa by President
Pascal Lissouba, which was described by Lissouba's rival, General
Denis Sassou N'guesso, as "a direct involvement of Kinshasa in the
conflict" of the Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
At the United Nations Security Council in New York, France
proposed on September 26 sending an international peacekeeping
force to Brazzaville under the UN flag, which was strongly opposed
by the United States. 
