<HEADLINE> Telstra Launches Australia's 1rst Internet Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Australia's telecommunications
giant Telstra Corp today officially launched a new Internet
commerce product which it said would allow customers to buy
products and services with confidence on the web.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Moriarty, chief executive officer with Telstra
Multimedia, launched SureLink, a trading tool which Moriarty said
assured total security for credit card transactions.
</P>
<P>
Moriarty said it was the first electronic commerce product of
its kind in Australia.
</P>
<P>
However, the move has already been described as a
"disappointment" by other industry players trying to establish
secured electronic transactions (SET).
</P>
<P>
They say Telstra's move jumps the gun on SET, which is being
backed by the likes of Microsoft, Visa and Mastercard.
</P>
<P>
SET is being established as a non-profit merchant trading
system while Telstra's Surelink service charges a fee, with
Telstra hoping it will secure a burgeoning supply of
transaction-based fee revenue.
</P>
<P>
"SET is coming on at fairly rapid rate, I'm not sure why
Telstra is not more committed," said Greg Storey, head of VisaNet
Services, part of Visa International.
</P>
<P>
"It provides merchants small and large with the mechanism for
commercializing their websites," said Moriarty.
</P>
<P>
Merchants have to sign-up to the program and Telstra has no
plans to extend this to international merchants, meaning global
shopping on the web via SureLink is not on offer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
