<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garbage Collection Modernized in Guangzhou of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Guangzhou, south
China, are joining the local "garbage revolution" by taking their
trash out every night rather than leaving it in dustbins for
sanitation workers to collect.
</P>
<P>
The new form of trash pick-up has been underway since the
beginning of the year in the Liwan District of Guangzhou, capital of
south China's Guangdong Province, and is rapidly becoming popular
in the other seven urban districts in Guangzhou, according to
Guangzhou Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Dustbins have been used in Guangzhou for more than 20 years.
The city plans to eliminate its 30,000 dustbins, which
seriously pollute the city and are the cause of frequent
complaints from local residents.
</P>
<P>
Sanitation workers now will go door-to-door to collect bagged
garbage, then compress it before hauling it away.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the daily 5,000 tons of garbage produced in the
city, Guangzhou will build 120 garbage compression
centers within three years, each covering an area of more than 100
square meters, according to an official. It also has closed its
over 1,500 dustbin storage centers, he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, The city plans to build 53 garbage compression
centers this year, 16 of which have already been completed. And
garbage trucks using advanced technology for compression are to be
used, the official said.
</P>
<P>
More than half of Guangzhou's citizens will be participating in
the new trash collection program by the end of this year, the
official promised.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
