<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Countdown Starts for Damming Yangtze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The countdown has begun for the
damming of the Yangtze River from November 6-8, a project designed
to make way for the world's largest hydro-electric endeavor.
</P>
<P>
Sources said today that the damming would be the most difficult
job of its kind in the world. When the work begins, the scheduled
flow volume will stand at 14,000 to 19,400 cubic meters per
second, the most ever reported in the world in the course of
damming a river for building a hydro-electric station.
</P>
<P>
Fearing that high tides and surging water in the Three Gorges
as well as complicated geological conditions, might cause problems,
scientists said that essential steps must be taken to deal with
potential collapse or leaking of the cofferdams.
</P>
<P>
As there are usually drastic changes of flow and water levels
in winter, engineers and workers are braced for any complications,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Two parallel cofferdams on both banks of the river have been
operating smoothly since last November. The final damming of the
river will need to sink great amounts of earth and rocks into the
river to connect the two cofferdams. After the work is completed,
the Yangtze will be forced to change its course.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the mouth of the river has been narrowed from 800
meters to just 360 meters, and it is expected to be further
narrowed to 130 meters by the end of October, according to He
Gong, deputy general manager of the China Yangtze River Three
Gorges Project Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day damming process, some 210,000 cubic meters
of earth and rocks are required to be sunk into the river to block
the mouth, he said. The biggest rock weighs three to five tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Rise in Forest Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- China has to date fulfilled some
95 percent of its afforestation goal for this year, with an
estimated 4.2 million hectares of trees planted across the country
during the past nine months, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3.7 million hectares of trees, over 90 percent of the
total, were planted through ground afforestation, while the rest
of the work was done by aerial seeding, the English newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that at present, Tianjin, the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region and 14 other provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions have completed or exceeded their own objectives
for tree-planting.
</P>
<P>
"The achievements were due to increases in manpower and
investment, the leading role played by key projects, the
employment of improved technology and the introduction of the
market economy across the country," the newspaper quoted an
official with the Ministry of Forestry as saying.
</P>
<P>
It said that 10 key afforestation projects received top
priority this year. They include the Shelter Belt Project in
northeast, north and northwest China, the Huaihe River-Taihu Lake,
Pearl River, Yellow River middle reaches and Liaohe River projects.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of this year's task, the Ministry of Forestry
called for new projects to be carried out and great efforts to be
made to protect forestry resources.
</P>
<P>
"Effective preservation of existing forests is the most
economical and efficient way to improve the environment," Minister
of Forestry Chen Yaobang was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government recently vowed to control soil erosion
and develop ecologically sound agriculture, so as to turn the
country, especially the northwestern regions, into a more
prosperous and beautiful place in the early years of the next
century.
</P>
<P>
China Daily said that the forest coverage rate in China is
expected to rise to 15.5 percent by the year 2000, compared with
the present 13.92 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
