<HEADLINE> Australian Opposition Accused for Travel Rorts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government today
claimed victory in the battle over travel rorts after Prime
Minister John Howard accused opposition leader Kim Beazley of
fudging the facts to protect his Senate deputy leader Nick Sherry.
</P>
<P>
Howard ended the fortnight of tit-for-tat allegations on the
front foot over Senate Sherry's 320 Australian dollars a night
claims for staying with his mother at Opossum Bay, 49 kilometers
from Hobart, Tasmania.
</P>
<P>
Howard ignored pressure for a truce after being forced last
week to sack three ministers and two key staffers over an apparent
cover-up of travel allowance repayments.
</P>
<P>
The travel allowance scandal was revealed last week when
Opposition leader Beazley in parliament called for resignation of
the Transport Minister John Sharp for wrongfully claiming 47
nights 8,740 Australian dollars (6,292 US dollars) travel
allowance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister for Administrative Services David Jull and
two of high-ranking officials in the prime minister office were
also forced to quit after being accused of covering up the
scandals.
</P>
<P>
Two days later, Minister for Science and Technology Peter
McGauran was forced to resign after admitting to mistaken travel
claims of about 1,400 Australian dollars (1,008 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Howard has the chance today to fire back against Beazley of
weakness for failing to apply the same standards to Senator Sherry
and attacked what he said was a cut-and-paste job on bureaucratic
definitions to justify his claims.
</P>
<P>
Labor deputy leader Gareth Evans said both sides had suffered
under the public brawling, "the battlefield is littered with
bodies on one side, a couple of flesh wounds on the other."
</P>
</TEXT>
