<HEADLINE> EU FMs Formally Sign Amsterdam Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Amsterdam, October 2 (Xinhua) -- A new treaty was formally signed
by the European Union (EU)'s foreign ministers or their
representatives here today to replace the EU's Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Amsterdam Treaty, which was signed at the Royal Palace of
Amsterdam, is scheduled to enter into force on January 1 of 1999 at the
earlist date after its ratification by national parliaments of the
15 EU member states.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was attended Thursday by Dutch Prime
Minister Wim Kok, President of the European Commission Jacques
Santer, President of the European Council Jean-Claude Juncker and
Jose-Maria Gil-Robles, president of the European Parliament, in the
presence of the Dutch Queen Beatrix and Prince Claus.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the new treaty which is supposed to complement and
replace the old one, is regarded as a low-key affair by EU
observers.
</P>
<P>
The signed voluminous document contains a version of the
Amsterdam Treaty which has been translated into all the languages of
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Considered less ambitious than its predecessor, the new treaty
pays more attention to diverse national interests of the 15 EU
member states and the reform of EU institutions than to an
enlarged EU.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that the new treaty could hardly be
regarded as a success since the negotiations on the revision of the
Maastricht Treaty were believed to be started at an inappropriate early
date when the EU had not yet recovered from the injury inflicted by
the ratification of the Maastricht Treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
