<HEADLINE> Devoted Doctors of Beijing Emergency Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Devoted doctors of the Beijing
Emergency Medical Center usually have to work many hours in a row
and can hardly snatch some time for a rest, according to today's
"China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The paper attributed this to the fact that the center is the
only one of its kind providing pre-hospital medical care in
Beijing. A 24-hour health emergency hotline is available for
patients in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
Every day the center generally has to deal with about 100
emergencies, sometimes about 300 cases per day, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
"It is really a full-time job. No weekends, nor holidays,"
Doctor Wang Haoran of the center was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Words couldn't describe how tired I was at that time," said
another doctor named Bi Dongxiang, when recalling a rescue work
that lasted till 11 o'clock in the evening.
</P>
<P>
But most of them have been used to this kind of life, saying
that all the hard work is worth it when a life is saved. "Doctors
enjoy great sense of fulfilment," said Bi.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment in 1988, the center has saved many
lives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
