<HEADLINE> Telephone Charges Up in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's telecommunications
company ZAMTEL has increased its telephone charges for
international and local calls in some cases by more than 100
percent with trunk calls shooting up by 900 Kwacha (about 69 US
cents) per minute, Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a circular released by ZAMTEL as saying the
charges became effective from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The charge for trunk calls has gone up from 600 (about 46
cents) to 1500 Kwacha (1.15 US dollars) per minute. The dealers'
price has been pegged at 1200 Kwacha (92 cents). Local calls will
now cost 300 Kwacha (23 cents) per minute from 100 Kwacha (7
cents) while the dealers' price is 240 Kwacha (18 cents), the
circular said.
</P>
<P>
Telephone, fax, and telex charges for destinations such as
Brazil, the United Arab Emirates and Cuba is now 20,030 Kwacha
(15.4 dollars) per minute. Distance calls to Pakistan and other
Asian countries are charged at 19,007 Kwacha (14.6 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The hike of telephone charges, the paper said, is attributed
to the growing strength of the U.S. dollars against the local
currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
