<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
drifted to a slightly lower close today, supported by the banking
sector and a few key bluechips, with volumes reflecting a lack of
investor interest.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index retreated from opening highs spurred
by a rise on Wall Street overnight to finish the day 1.1 points
lower at 2778.1 points.
</P>
<P>
The looming Telstra Corp float had caused investors to hang off
buying stocks, cashing up instead to take part in the first stage
of privatization of the telecommunications giant, Nevitts broker
Steve Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
"The Telstra float is sucking a bit of money out of the market.
We have seen a little bit of selling for that," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Federal Government announced the 8-10 billion US
dollar float of one third of Telstra with the guarantee that at
least 70 percent of the offer would go to Australian investors.
The offer opens on October 15.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index shaved off 6.0 points to finish at
4556.5 points while the banking sector was buoyed by the National
Australia Bank's (NAB) announcement yesterday that it had bought
the County Natwest Investment Management Ltd, Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
The banking index jumped 52 points to 5479.1. NAB shares were
60 cents stronger at 21.75 Australian dollars, Commonwealth shares
climbed 10 cents to 17.07 Australian dollars, ANZ bank added 11
cents to 11.39 Australian dollars, while Westpac bucked the trend,
dropping five cents to 8.58 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished 3.3 points higher at 1380.2,
following stronger gold prices yesterday, Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 1.7 points to 1355.5, after yesterday's
surge.
</P>
<P>
Global media company Rupert Murdoch's News Corp finished steady
at 7.00 Australian dollars with its preferred shares easing five
cents to 6.14 Australian dollars. Kerry Packer's Publishing and
Broadcasting slumped nine cents to 9.00 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 398.36 million shares, worth 662.4
million US dollars, with falls outweighing rises 558 to 550.
</P>
