<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Philipines Sign Tax Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has signed a treaty with the
Philipines aimed at avoiding the incidence of double taxation, local
newspaper This Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, signed in Manila on Monday, is described as a further
step of Nigeria in its determination to enter into economic
cooperation with Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Nigeria's Finance Minister Anthony Ani, the treaty is
a "landmark" in the two countries' bilateral relations and "will create
the stable economic climate conducive to the free flow of trade and
technology" between them.
</P>
<P>
Double taxation has been a huge disincentive to businessmen from
the two countries to invest in the other side.
</P>
<P>
There are now over 15,000 Filipino nationals working in Nigeria in
the fields of education, missionary activities, engineering and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
The Philipines mainly exports jeeps, leather goods, garments and
footwear to Nigeria, while imports petroleum, cotton, chemicals and
refined lead from the latter.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which has been on the negotiation table since 1981,
will help "remove all inhibitions which double taxation normally
imposes on growth of trade and free movement of persons between the
two countries," said Ani.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, Nigeria has turned to the east to make new
friends, forced by the difficulties resulted from the sanctions
imposed by its former western allies in Europe and America, and has
benefited from the strategic shift.
</P>
<P>
The country's head of state, General Sani Abacha, said Wednesday
that Nigeria will continue to make new friends in other parts of the
world with those who wish to be friends and cooperate with it on the
basis of mutual understanding, trust and respect.
</P>
<P>
Ani also explained Nigeria's economic shift towards the Southeast
Asian nations, saying that from the many advantage of South-South
coopertion, the Asian countries have middle level technology which is
likely to be easily adapted by Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Nigeria and most of the Asian Tigers were in the same
economic siutation about three decade ago, the minister said, Nigeria
is in a better position to learn from the developmental experience of
these countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0122 </DOCNO>
