<HEADLINE> Malaysia Suggests Regional Forest Fires Monitoring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has proposed the
setting up of a monitoring system at the ASEAN level to prevent
forest fires, Primary Industries Minister Lim Keng Yaik said
today.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion was made during a United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) meeting recently, the minister told reporters after
opening the Fourth Conference on Forestry and Forest Products
Research at the Forest Research Institute of Malaysia here.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore and parts of the
Philippines and Thailand have been blanketed by a thick and smoky
haze generated from the raging forest fires in Indonesia affecting
up to 800,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Lim said, "We should have a monitoring system because these
forest fires are bound to happen again and again." But he did not
say when or how the system would operate.
</P>
<P>
"If you monitor before it becomes big, you can avoid a regional
or international disaster (like the haze)," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lim said huge forest fires like the ones in Indonesia could
have been avoided if the situation was closely monitored.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, which was worst affected by Indonesia's forest fires,
has sent more than 1,000 firefighters to Indonesia to help put out
the fires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
