<HEADLINE> Nigeria Signs Oil Deals With Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will supply 20,000
barrels of crude oil daily to neighbouring Guinea, Mali, Niger,
the Republic of Benin and Cote d'Ivoire, according to term
contracts signed recently.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Times newspaper said today that the new contracts
are in line with the spirit of strengthening ties among members
of the Economic Community of West African States.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Nigeria had earlier signed similar
contracts with Gambia, Ghana and Togo, with a daily export of
60,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
Industry observers were quoted as saying that the new deal
also marked a gradual shift in the exports of Nigeria's crude oil
in the spot market to term contract.
</P>
<P>
While the Nigeria National Petroleum Corporation which
controls the country's oil resources favors spot market, the
National Economic Intelligence Committee has been pressing for
term contracts which encourages transparency and accountability,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's is Africa's largest oil producer, with a daily oil
export estimated at 2.18 million barrels in the first half of
1997. 
</P>
