<HEADLINE> UN to Compensate Egyptian Workers 84 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Governing Council of the
United Nations Compensation Commission (UNCC) has decided to award
900,000 Egyptian workers with over 84 million U.S. dollars for
their funds frozen in Iraqi banks in early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The total of 84,393,992 dollars will be distributed through the
Egyptian government to those claimants, who have been seeking
compensation of funds deposited in Iraqi banks for transfer to
beneficiaries in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of these funds ceased after August 2, 1990.
</P>
<P>
During its 25th session from September 29 to October 1, the
UNCC reviewed the original 1.24 million individual claims by those
Egyptian workers and determined that 223,817 claims did not fall
within the commission's jurisdiction, said a UNCC press release.
</P>
<P>
The UNCC, established in 1991, is a subsidiary organ of the
U.N. Security Council to decide claims submitted by victims of
Iraq's invasion and occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
UNCC's decision on Egyptian workers brings the total number of
claims resolved by the commission to over 2.4 million, out of over
2.6 million filed with the commission since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The total compensation so far approved by the UNCC is over 6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The next UNCC session is scheduled for December 15-17, 1997,
the press release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
