<HEADLINE> Zambia's Prison Service Goes Commercial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Fiftythree prisons in Zambia
began planting cash crops to raise extra funds to feed its
inmates, Zambia News agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted prisons Acting Commissioner Philip Sinyangwe
as saying in Kabwe, central Zambia, on Tuesday that his
department will also start experimenting on paprica crop at some
farms this planting season.
</P>
<P>
The department has decided to go into commercial farming
because it is the only source of revenue to enable it look after
13,000 inmates in the country, Sinyangwe said.
</P>
<P>
The prison department has already paid for drilling of two
boreholes at Mwembeshi farm for crop irrigation, and if the
experiment succeed, the growing of paprica could spread to other
prison farms.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to teach prisoners to produce what they expect
to eat and not punishing them when we tell them to work on the
land as some people may think," he said.
</P>
<P>
The department hopes to export the crop to foreign market next
year and earn foreign exchange, Sinyangwe added.
</P>
<P>
Prison department also wants to venture into cattle ranching
by grouping its animals from several farm in one place, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
