<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bovine TB Epidemic in S. African Park No Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The bovine tuberculosis
epidemic sweeping Kruger National Park, which is situated between
South Africa and Mozambique, poses no threat to local animals and
visitors to the park, a conservation expert said.
</P>
<P>
"It's only the older infected animals that die," local daily
The Star quoted the park's senior Conservation Manager Johan van
der Merwe as saying today.
</P>
<P>
A 200km-long, 2.8m-high electrified fence being built around
sections of the park at the cost of seven million Rand (1.48
million U.S. Dollars) would ensure the disease stay within the
park, Merwe said.
</P>
<P>
TB came to the Kruger National Park in the 1960s when a herd
of infected cattle spread the disease to buffalo, said the
manager, adding that only animals in the southern parts of the
park were infected.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic, which posed no danger to human health, could
only be transmitted by drinking the infected cattle's milk which
has not been pasteurized, or by slaughtering diseased cattle
without wearing gloves, Merwe noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
