<HEADLINE> Pudong Seeks Overseas Investment for Massive Infrastructure Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Pudong New Area, a booming
financial and trade zone in Shanghai, is seeking overseas funding
for seven infrastructure projects involving a total investment of
nearly 10 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pudong is applying for overseas government loans and
World Bank loans for the projects, according to local official
sources.
</P>
<P>
Pudong will provide preferential treatment to overseas
investors involved in construction of the local infrastructure
projects, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The projects include the first phase of the Pudong
International Airport, the second line of the Pudong Metro System,
the Pudong International Deep-Water Port, the second phase of the
Waigaoqiao Thermal Power Plant, the Outer-Circle line of
Shanghai's Urban Highway, the second phase of Shanghai's Sewage
Treatment Plant, and the expansion of Pudong's switchboard
handling capacity and service network for mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
The Pudong International Airport, to be completed in the year
1999, will require 1.2 billion dollars in total investment.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will also need nearly three billion dollars to build a
highway system to ease its traffic jams, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Pudong New Area Urban Construction Bureau is in charge of
contract negotiations with overseas investors, the officials
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
