<HEADLINE> Philippine Government, Rebels Discuss Rules For Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the Philippine
government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) met
in the southern Philippine city of Cotabato today to discuss
initial ground rules for implementing a general ceasefire in
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency said the government panel was led by
Maj. Gen. Joselin Nazareno, chief of the army's 4th Infantry
Division, while the MILF panel was led by Lawyer Omar Umpar.
</P>
<P>
Aside from discussing the ceasefire rules, the report said, the
negotiators will also assess if government troops have complied
with a condition agreed upon by both parties last month in Rajah
Muda, Pikit, Cotabato, for the complete pull-out of troops.
</P>
<P>
The MILF requested an investigation on the matter after reports
said that government troops were still seen in the area.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group warned that it would suspend future talks with
the government if the troops are still there.
</P>
<P>
The MILF became a major threat to peace in Mindanao, the
southern Philippines, following a peace accord between the
government and the rebel Moro National Liberation Front in
September last year.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which has vowed to continue its fight for an
independent state in Mindanao, reached a general ceasefire with
the government in July this year, but rules for the implementation
of the truce have to be discussed and worked out.
</P>
<P>
The current meeting, the eighth in the series of low-level
talks, is expected to end on Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
