<HEADLINE> World Bank Gives Zambia Loans for Road Repairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has given Zambia
a loan of about 91 billion Kwacha (70 million U.S.Dollars) to
finance the initial road repairs in Lusaka as part of the
country-wide exercise under the road sector investment program,
Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Raymond Jhala, Chairman of the National Roads
Board through which the loan was granted, as saying at a press
briefing Wednesday that the board will from now on carry out
regular maintenance of rehabilitated roads which is not done in
the past contributing to the current high level of deterioration
of the road network.
</P>
<P>
Under the 10-year investment program which was launched with
the repair of Lusaka roads, Zambia will offer regular maintemance
to roads apart from merely rehabilitating them.
</P>
<P>
Most of the roads in Zambia has not been attended to for over
30 years despite the fact that road needs to be rehabilitated
every five years.
</P>
<P>
Jhala said one of the contributing factors to the destruction
of roads is overloaded heavy duty vehicles, and bridges need to
be replaced because they were constructed with ancient
technology.
</P>
<P>
He said that the initial five years of the repair exercise
requirs about 385 million dollars, part of which will be raised
from road users. 
</P>
</TEXT>
