<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Horticulture Exports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean horticulture
producers exported more than 2,000 tons of cut flower and fresh
produce valued in excess of 120 million Zimbabwe dollars (10
million US Dollars) since the 1997/98 marketing season began in
July.
</P>
<P>
Horticultural Promotion Council (HPC) Chief Executive Stanley
Heri said on Wednesday the marketing season had started well with
418 tons of flower and 1,727 tons of fresh produce exported to
date.
</P>
<P>
"Flowers and fresh produce have earned the industry 58 million
(4.8 million US Dollars) and 64 million Zimbabwe Dollars (5.3
million dollars) respectively and we expect to earn 1.7 billion
Zimbabwe Dollars (141.6 million dollars) this season," Heri said.
</P>
<P>
Estimates in volume terms for the 1997/98 season stood at
17,290 tons and 12,240 tons for flower and fresh produce
respectively, a significant increase from last year's exports,
according to the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
Between July 1996 and June 1997, Zimbabwe exported a total of
13,800 tons of cut flowers and 9,800 tons of fresh produce worth
about 1.2 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (about 100 million US
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Competition continued to increase on the international markets
and local growers have been urged to increase production so as to
maximize earnings, in addition to seek for new markets.
</P>
<P>
But a major concern, apart from growing competition, is the
rising freight costs which now constituted over 50 percent of
total input costs for production.
</P>
<P>
At present there are more than 1,000 commercial horticultural
producers registered with HPC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blasts Rock Indian Train, Killing 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Triple blasts in an Indian
train bound for Amritsar, Punjab, on Wednesday night left at least
seven people dead and another 20 injured, most of them seriously,
the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Among the injured are four Australians and one Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The three blasts rocked the train within 20 minutes near
Ghaziabad, Uttar Pradesh, which is about 50 kilometers east of New
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
The first of the series of blasts took place at 8:45 p.m. local
time, the second and most intensive blast occurred ten minutes
later while the last blast was at 9:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The first blast was of low intensity and was in Coach S-6 of
the train. The foreigners injured were traveling in this
compartment.
</P>
<P>
The second blast ripped the coach apart as the train officials
were in the process of getting the passengers evacuated. The blast
was the most damaging, leaving a gaping hole in the floor of the
compartment.
</P>
<P>
Minutes thereafter, when most of the train had been cleared of
passengers, a third blast took place. This was in another coach
and caused some damage to the seats.
</P>
<P>
It was later confirmed that at least seven people had been
killed in the blasts. All the injured have been rushed to
hospitals in Ghaziabad.
</P>
<P>
The police are investigating the nature of the blasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
