<HEADLINE> East Africa Seeks Identical Asylum Legislations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Senior immigration
officials and refugees chiefs of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania have
recommended reconciliation of the existing asylum procedures in
the three east African countries.
</P>
<P>
The officials called for the formation of data banks to record
movements in the region, today's Daily News reported.
</P>
<P>
The officials made the call at a two-day meeting which ended
in Arusha in northern Tanzania on Wednesday. They suggested that
the permanent tripartite committee of the East African
Co-operation work out a mechanism for harmonization of
legislation on all aspects of refugees.
</P>
<P>
They also urged exchange of visits in a bid to enhance
practical handling of matters related to refugees from Rwanda,
Burundi, Somalia and other neighboring countries and asylum
seekers in the region.
</P>
<P>
They advised the east African universities having teaching and
outreach programs on forced immigration to coordinate their
efforts from a regional point of view and make effective use of
the Inter-University Council for EA.
</P>
<P>
The much awaited EA passports, which were originally scheduled
for delivery late last month, has now been shelved to next month.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, however, agreed that final specimens of the
passports be availed to immigration chiefs for approval before
production commences.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was informed that Kenya and Uganda have
re-introduced inter-state passes which are ready for issuance.
Tanzania is also in the process of printing her inter-state
passes, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It said the member states have implemented the decision of the
seventh tripartite commission to remove road blocks from
desinated EA cooperation networks subject to maintaining
temporary ones required for security measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
