<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Garment Export to Rise 20 Percent A Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The volume of ready-made garment
(RMG) export from Bangladesh is likely to increase at a rate of 20
percent per annum up to 2005.
</P>
<P>
This statement was made Wednesday at a meeting by Mostofa Golam
Quddus, president of the Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and
Exports Association (BGMEA).
</P>
<P>
The RMG sector had earned over three billion U.S. dollars in
the last 1996-97 fiscal year which constituted about 68 percent of
Bangladesh's total export earnings, the BGMEA chief stated, adding
the sector had brought about a tremendous prospect for the
investment in weaving sector with its own progress.
</P>
<P>
"The RMG sector has ensured the use of over 2.6 billion yards
(about 2.38 billion meters) of fabric annually and demand of it is
increasing every year at a rate of 20 percent," he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that about 60 percent of woven fabrics
now used in the RMG sector are imported.
</P>
<P>
Tremendous possibilities had been created for foreign investors
to invest in Bangladesh because of non-availability of domestic
capital and gradual increase of use of fabrics in the RMG sector,
the BGMEA president said.
</P>
<P>
"Favorable investment infrastructure, low inflation rate,
easily trainable vast labor force and flourishment of some new
generation entrepreneurs have turned the country's RMG sector into
the highest prospective investment focal point in South Asia," the
BGMEA chief stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
