<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Hold Referendum in Eastern Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Cabinet has
decided a referendum will be held in two major cities in Eastern
province for the people there to decide whether to merge with
Northern province or not, Justice Minister G.L. Peiris said here
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly news conference, the minister said
President Chandrika Kumaratunga and all the 29 government
ministers attending Monday's special cabinet meeting had agreed to
hold a referendum in Trincomalee and Batticaloa, two of the
biggest cities in Eastern province.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after the cabinet devoted five hours to
discussing the devolution proposals, a package aimed at realizing
peace with the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) by granting
more autonomy to Northern and Eastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
Peiris said that the move is for the people there, the majority
of whom are Tamils, to decide whether they will merge with
Northern province or not. In Eastern province, the Tamils make up
41 percent of the population, the Muslims 32.2 percent and the
Sinhalese 24.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister didn't specify when and how the referendum will be
held.
</P>
<P>
He said if the people in the two cities choose not to merge
with the north, the government will take steps to maintain the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting an ethnic war with the government
for a separate state of their own in the north and east of the
country, where Tamils make up almost two-thirds of the total
population with Sinhalese occupying 13.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the whole nation, Sinhalese make up about 74 percent of the
population and Tamils come to 18 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
