<HEADLINE> Thai PM Caught Between Coalition Allies, Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyuhd has been caught between coalition allies and
influential factions in his own New Aspiration Party in the issue
of a cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Chatichai Choonhavan, former prime minister and leader of the
Chart Pattana Party, the second largest party in the government,
said Wednesday that without a quick reshuffle of the cabinet the
country's economy will suffer further damage, and a reshuffle
could not wait because the economy was at stake.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chavalit is facing intense lobbying from ministers
who are considered to be likely to be replaced in the expected
shake-up.
</P>
<P>
Among those badly attacked in the censure debate last week was
Deputy Prime Minister Sukhavich Rangsitpol, who was alleged to be
involved in irregularities in the purchase of computers for
schools.
</P>
<P>
There has been pressure to dismiss him from the cabinet, but
the prime minister finds it hard to remove him, as he is a deputy
leader of the prime minister's New Aspiration Party and has the
support of a faction, known as the August 17 faction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prime minister is selecting suitable non-MP
professionals to take up posts in the cabinet, but there are
reports that some of those who have been approached are unwilling
to join a government which has suffered confidence crisis because
of mismanagement of the economy.
</P>
<P>
What is more, the government has only a few months to go before
a new general election, expected in May next year, in line with
the new Constitution, which was approved by Parliament late last
month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
