<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Facing Crisis Over Draft Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Despite a possible collapse of his
center-left coalition, Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi today
rejected demands from his ally -- the Communist Refoundation party
-- to re-write his 1998 draft budget.
</P>
<P>
"I always keep the dialogue open but in the firmness of the
contents of the budget," Prodi told reporters after more than one
hour of talks with President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, who has the
sole right to dissolve parliament.
</P>
<P>
Prodi unveiled the draft budget at the weekend, which the
government considers essential to secure Italy's membership of the
single European currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
But Refoundation, a hard-left party which has ensured Prodi's
majority in the Lower House, says the budget contains unacceptable
cuts in welfare and pensions.
</P>
<P>
Refoundation's decision to oppose the 25-trillion-lira budget
put in jeopardy both the budget and the future of the 17-month-old
Prodi government.
</P>
<P>
Asked if there were room for negotiation, Prodi said, "I don't
know. I hope there is room for reason."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted, "It is impossible to re-write the budget,
which was thought out by the entire government. But Adaptations
are possible."
</P>
<P>
Prodi also rejected the option of forming a new parliamentary
majority, saying he had come to power with "a clear program and a
clear majority."
</P>
<P>
Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi told the Senate
this evening that Italy had made progress in its economic
development in the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
He noted that interest rates and inflation have been falling
and the deficit-gross domestic product ratio has declined from
seven percent to a level "fully compatible with the three percent
called for in the Maastricht Treaty."
</P>
<P>
However, the political crisis is unfavorable to Prodi
government because the Refoundation party is insisting that talks
with the government can begin only when the government withdraw
the draft budget.
</P>
<P>
And the opposition parties are busy assessing the political
prospect and contacting each other in a bid to coordinate their
moves. 
</P>
