<HEADLINE> Thailand's Consumer Prices Increase in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Consumer prices in Thailand were
up 7 percent year-on-year in September, compared with 6.5 percent
for the previous month, according to the Thai commerce ministry.
</P>
<P>
Inflation as measured by the consumer price index (CPI) was 4.5
percent in the first half of the year, but was expected to head
toward double digits by the end of the year because of the impact
of the baht's depreciation, the ministry was quoted today by local
press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The CPI for the first nine months of this year showed a rise of
5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Narong chai Akrasanee predicted the
year-on-year index would be kept below 7 percent as required by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in exchange for its
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
A 1-percent rise in the non-food sector and a decline of 0.1
percent in the food and beverage sector were factors in the
increase between August and September.
</P>
<P>
Also, due to the value-added tax increase from 7 percent to 10
percent on August 16, there had been sharp price rises for
clothes, some services, oil, building materials and stationery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
