<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Commerce Minister Urges Rice Export Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Thai Commerce Minister
Narongchai Akrasanee has proposed forcing Thai rice farmers,
millers and exporters to register their product to prevent
adulteration, a ministry source said today.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is aimed at registering the origin of fragrant
rice, also known as jasmine rice, in order to control the quality
of rice, which is one of the major agricultural exports of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, if supported by the Ministry of Agriculture and
Cooperatives, will be the first one in Thailand to register the
origin of its agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
High overseas demand, particularly in East Asia, has pushed up
the export price of Thai fragrant rice to over 750 U.S. Dollars
per ton, about 300 dollars more per ton than other types of white
rice.
</P>
<P>
The commerce minister has been deeply concerned about the
rampant adulteration of fragrant rice with low-quality rice.
</P>
<P>
Although the depreciation of the baht has resulted in favorable
export prices, the rampant adulteration of fragrant rice has
dented the image of Thai fragrant rice exporters, leading to
cancellation of orders for fragrant rice in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Commerce Ministry proposed that millers and
exporters use 5-kg package, instead of 100-kg sacks, to prevent
adulteration during the re-packaging process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
