<HEADLINE> Thailand to Add Nothing to Financial Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will add nothing to its
financial liberalization program under the General Agreement of
Trade in Services (GATS due to be signed in December in Geneva,
Thai Deputy Finance Minister Chaovarat Charnveerakul said.
</P>
<P>
The GATS will cover market access, national treatment and
regulations, and service liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Chaovarat made the comment Wednesday after his meeting with a
12-member delegation from the US-ASEAN Business Council which has
formed a group to study ways of investing in high-potential
countries, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Even though the delegation wants Thailand to liberalize to a
greater extent than it did under the temporary GATS reached in
1995, Chaovarat insisted that the country had nothing to add to
what had been agreed then, given the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Thailand needed to upgrade its systems to
control and examine the local financial institutions before
deciding to make the country's financial sector more open and
free.
</P>
<P>
The commitments made in 1995 include allowing foreign investors
to hold up to 25 percent in Thai financial institutions, the
opening of the Bangkok International Banking Facilities, and an
attempt to award more licenses to set up commercial banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
