<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Concerned Over Social Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Enrique Cardoso called on South American countries to show more
concern over their social problems, Chilean newspapers reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Chilean press, Cardoso said that
eliminating social inequality and improving the living standard of
the people, the quality of education and the political situation
should receive their top priority.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso arrived in Santiago on Tuesday to attend a meeting of
the Pacific Economic Cooperation Council (PECC), which is a
semi-governmental organization established in 1980 and comprising
22 countries and regions on the Pacific rim. Brazil is one of the
three observer countries of the PECC.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian president noted that as the United States is not
paying enough attention to these problems, "so it is up to us" to
solve them.
</P>
<P>
On the future of the South American Common Market (Mercosur),
Cardoso said that Mercosur grows faster than any other trade bloc
on the American Continent.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, the largest trading bloc in South America, groups
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay. Chile and Bolivia are
associated members.
</P>
<P>
"Trade between Brazil and Argentina went up from 3 billion
U.S. dollars to 15 billion dollars in a period of just four to
five years," he said.
</P>
<P>
As to the forthcoming 2nd Summit of Americas to be held next
April in Santiago, Cardoso said, "I think it is all up to us to
work out an agenda which will include something more than taxes
and tariffs."
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian president also called for a permanent seat for
Latin America in the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The 12th PECC General Meeting, attended by about 800 officials,
businessmen and researchers, opened on Tuesday and will end on
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
