<HEADLINE> Thailand Needs More Budget Cut to Meet IMF Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will need to cut
another 100 billion baht (2.74 billion U.S. dollars) from its
fiscal 1998 budget to meet the target set by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The IMF, which is supervising Thailand's economic performance
as a condition for providing a 17.2 billion dollar standby credit
to Thailand, has requested Thailand to achieve a budget surplus of
1 percent of the country's gross domestic product in the 1998
fiscal year, which began on October 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 spending budget totals 823 billion baht (22.53 billion
dollars), with a revenue target of 873 billion baht (23.9 billion
dollars), leaving an expected budget surplus of 50 billion baht (
1.37 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry, Budget Bureau, National Economic and
Social Development Board and the Bank of Thailand will meet this
week to determine the exact amount that is to be cut, the Bangkok
Post reported today.  
