<HEADLINE> Foreign Spies Using Canadian Passports Unacceptable: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said today that it would be totally unacceptable for any
foreign spies to use Canadian passports.
</P>
<P>
Chretien made the comment in the House of Commons today when he
was asked about two Canadian passport holders arrested in Jordan
over an attempted murder of a leader of the Islamic militant group
Hamas.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is completely unacceptable to this government that
anybody authorized by the government would use the Canadian
passport to perpetrate any illegal action as they have done,"
Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
He told the lawmakers that the Canadian authorities are talking
to officials in Israel and in Jordan to find out what had happened.
</P>
<P>
Hamas political chief Khaled Meshal was assaulted outside his
office in Amman last Thursday and the two attackers are reported
to be agents of Israel's secret service Mossad.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy said he will
discuss the issue with Jordan's foreign minister Thursday in New
York.
</P>
<P>
"I know it's a matter I have to treat seriously and that it's
of some concern to us that Canadian passports were being used in
this matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I want to find out exactly what took place and who is involved
and why," Axworthy noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister told reporters that he would speak to Jordanian
officials before talking to Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
He also vowed to take appropriate actions to make sure that the
integrity of the Canadian passport system be preserved. 
</P>
