<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major
Beijing-based newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- People of all ethnic groups across China yesterday
celebrated the 48th founding anniversary of the People's Republic
of China with flag-raising ceremonies and a variety of festivities.
</P>
<P>
Some 260,000 people gathered at Tiananmen Square in Beijing to
see the daily flag-raising ceremony held at the crack of
dawn. Deafening applause burst from the crowd when the Five-Star
Red Flag reached the top of the mast within about two minutes.
</P>
<P>
-- A solemn flag-raising ceremony was held in Hong Kong early
yesterday morning to mark the 48th National Day of the People's
Republic of China. This was the first official flag-raising
ceremony in Hong Kong dedicated to the Chinese National Day since
the region returned to the motherland on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 people gathered at the seafront site at the
Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center Extension to watch the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- The construction work at the Three Gorges Project on the
Yangtze River and the Xiaolangdi water control project on the
Yellow River are proceeding smoothly and are expected to dam the
two major rivers within two months.
</P>
<P>
 China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- Preparations for the return of Macao are in full swing and
are proceeding smoothly, said Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua
News Agency Macao Branch at a banquet marking the 48th anniversary
of the founding of the People's Republic of China yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"Macao's return to the embrace of the motherland in 1999 marks
another important step forward in the course of national
reunification (following the return of Hong Kong)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Daily
</P>
<P>
-- More than 300 compatriots from Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), Macao and Taiwan and overseas Chinese
and Chinese nationals from over 20 countries and regions attended
a reception in Beijing yesterday to mark the 48th founding
anniversary of the People's Repubic of China.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin welcomed them to Beijing and extended
cordial regards to them on behalf of the Municipal Committee of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) and his municipal government.
</P>
