<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Condemn SFOR's Seisure of Transmission Relays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb
member of Bosnia's Presidency, and Bosnian Serb government in Pale
on Wednesday condemned the multinational Stabilization Force's
taking control of three radio and television transmission relay
stations.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Karlos Vestendorp, high international
commissioner in Bosnia, the SFOR blockaded the relay stations in
Trebeviche, Udrigovo and Modrica on Wednesday morning, the
Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
Javier Solana, secretary general of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, said in Maastricht, the Netherlands, that the move
was designed to assist Vestendorp in ensuring that the media in
the Bosnian Serb republic reflects international norms of
professional media conduct and fully supports the goals of the
Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serb government held a meeting on the matter on
Wednesday, saying that the SFOR action is a premeditated move
designed to place the media under the control of Bosnian Serb
President Biljana Plavsic, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The local Bosnian Serb media loyal to war-time leader Radovan
Karadzic was blamed by NATO and other Western organizations as
inciting unrest against international presence.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic's successor, Plavsic, has the backing of the West.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik said that the SFOR move could lead to uncontrolled
moves of Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The Pale Radio-TV Director Miroslav Tohol said his staff would
take some non-military measures such as a hunger strike to protest
the SFOR action, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
