<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Judge Orders Alabama Department to Stop Segregation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A federal judge has ordered
the Department of Transportation of Alabama, the United States, to
stop segregating work crews, a practice the department continued
as it battled a 12-year-old racial discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge Myron Thompson in Montgomery ruled Tuesday
that segregated crews violate the 1964 Civil Rights Act, after
hearing a department division engineer testify about the all-black
and all-white crews.
</P>
<P>
Dalmus Lamar Davidson, responding to questions from an attorney
for black employees, said some workers of both races preferred the
segregated crews.
</P>
<P>
"There are individuals both black and white that want to stay
with either black or white crews," The Associated Press today
quoted Davidson, who is white, as saying.
</P>
<P>
In his ruling, Thompson said that crew assignments should not
be based on the racial preferences of employees. He ordered the
department to report to him by October 8 on steps taken to end the
policy.
</P>
<P>
Black employees sued 12 years ago, alleging racial bias in
hiring and promotions.
</P>
<P>
The state reached an agreement in 1994 to expand efforts to
hire and promote blacks. But black employees contend the state
has not lived up to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
In April, Thompson ordered the department to pay about 2,000
black employees some 34 million dollars in back pay. The state is
appealing.
</P>
<P>
The current phase of the trial is to determine what jobs, if
any, some black employees are entitled to as a result of
discrimination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
