<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Albanians Stage Demonstrations in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Ethnic Albanians staged a mass
anti-government demonstration today in the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo, prompting a quick condemnation from the Serbian government.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators, including students, teachers and some former
government officials, gathered in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo,
and six other areas of the province.
</P>
<P>
They were later dispersed by police using rubber bullets and
tear gas. Violent conflicts were reported in some areas.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, the Serbian government issued a
statement, denouncing the act as an attempt to split up the
country under the guise of ethnic issues.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the province's
population, have long been in conflict with Serbians.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo had been an autonomous province with its own provincial
assembly and government until 1990. After its autonomous status
was removed, ethnic Albanian politicians proclaimed Kosovo a
"republic".
</P>
<P>
The act was declared illegal by the Serbian and federal
authorities, who have since condemned any attempt to break up the
country and any foreign interference on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0197 </DOCNO>
