</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- The Labor Party's bloody campaign on travel allowances
backfired yesterday when one of its own frontbenchers admitted
claiming 43,000 Australian dollars (30,960 U.S. dollars) for
staying at his mother's house, as both sides of federal politics
sought to end the nine-day fiasco.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Rio Tinto's battle for power with the coal-mining union
spread across the entire Hunter Valley yesterday as 8,000 workers
at more than 40 collieries began a protest strike, marking a
serious escalation of industrial action at Rio Tinto's Hunter
Valley mines.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign minister Alexander Downer yesterday launched a
scathing attack on Amnesty International, accusing the
organization of ignorance in its latest criticisms of Australia's
human rights record.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's biggest export industry is facing massive
disruption, with 8,000 coal union members at 52 NSW mines striking
yesterday in protest against Rio Tinto issuing writs against union
officials and workers.  
</P>
