<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Urge Reversal of Decline Trend of Aid Flows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Development of the South
was not only an investment in peace and security but would clearly
rebound to the advantages of the countries of the North in the
long run, Abdus Samad Azad, foreign minister of Bangladesh, said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 52nd session of the General Assembly, the
foreign minister said global Official Development Aid flows
continued to slump and this trend must be reversed.
</P>
<P>
He said development of the South would mean bigger markets for
the exports of the countries of the North.
</P>
<P>
Azad said the plight of the Least Developed Countries (LDCs)
called for very careful consideration and had in the past merited
a special place and focus in the international agenda.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that two major international
conferences on LDCs had been held in the 80s and 90s and important
decisions and programs of actions adopted. The implementation of
those had been disappointing, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the Third UN Conference on LDCs should be held in the
year 2000 to chart the course of global support for these weakest
members at the start of the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
He urged special consideration and concessions for LDCs to
enable them to meet World Trade Organization deadlines.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also urged all major LDCs concerns to be
given most favorable consideration at the forthcoming high level
meeting in Geneva next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
