<HEADLINE> US Gov't Files Charges Against Unfair Trade Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government today
accused South Korea, Japan, Canada, the European Union and
Australia of unfair trade practices, kicking off a process that
could lead to trade sanctions against them.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here, U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky said she would also initiate the World Trade
Organization (WTO) cases against Japan on fruit, Canada and Europe
on dairy practices and against Australia on automotive leather.
</P>
<P>
The charge against South Korea for not opening big enough the
auto market came following long-time negotiations held over the
past several days in which the South Koreans sought to keep from
being singled out under a provision of the U.S. trade law known as
Super 301.
</P>
<P>
Under the provision, the president will be allowed to launch
investigations of unfair trade practices against countries and to
impose punitive tariffs if negotiations fail to remove the
barriers.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky announced that such a case was being brought against
South Korea because negotiations between the two countries had
failed to resolve all of the U.S. complaints.
</P>
<P>
She said that despite South Korea's commitments in 1995, sales
of foreign cars made up less that 1 percent of the South Korean
market.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States did not bring a case against Japan
on autos.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky also noted that the Super 301 review demonstrated
the administration's commitment to ensuring that other countries
live up to their commitments to remove trade barriers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Senate Panel Backs Clinton's Trade Powers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Senate panel voted
today to give President Bill Clinton special trade negotiating
powers, the first step toward approval of the authority the White
House requested to negotiate new trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Senate Finance Committee approved the measure by voice vote
with no public discussion.
</P>
<P>
"We are very pleased with the action taken today by the Senate
Finance Committee," U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky
said. "It was a strong bipartisan showing of support for fast
track legislation, for the power of the president to continue to
lead with respect to international economic policy."
</P>
<P>
The fast approval before the Finance Committee sends the
measure to an uncertain future in Congress. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott expressed concerns today about lack of Democratic
support in the Senate and House Speaker Newt Gingrich has said
that no more than 14 House Democrats are currently willing to
publicly commit to support for the proposal.
</P>
<P>
But the Clinton administration insists that it will begin to
pick up more support as business interests begin to make the case
for expanding free trade.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton is seeking the so-called fast-track
negotiating authority to expand the North American Free Trade
Agreement with Mexico to other countries in Latin America and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
But he has been criticized by labor unions and environmental
groups for emphasizing trade agreements over worker rights and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The negotiating authority allows the U.S. president to
negotiate trade agreements that the U.S. Congress can vote for or
against but not amend. The special authority owned by the U.S.
president expired in 1994 and President Clinton's request for
renewal has been controversial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US House Panel Approves Emergency Bill to Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House Education and
Workforce Committee today approved overwhelmingly an emergency
measure to help college students and graduates refinance their
student loans.
</P>
<P>
The measure, approved by a 43-0 vote in the committee, would
enable students to refinance their direct loans through private
lenders instead of the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
It was in response to severe problems the department and its
contractor, Electronic Data Systems Corporation, have had in
coping with a flood of applications.
</P>
<P>
The department in late August had to quit taking requests to
refinance its direct loans due to a backlog of tens of thousands
of applications.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which will be taken up by the full House later this
month and considered by the Senate after that, let borrowers get
the same favorable interest rates offered in the direct program.
</P>
<P>
The problems aroused dispute between the Republicans and the
Democrats. Republicans said the refinancing problems show that the
department cannot manage the direct lending program. They favor
the older, guaranteed-loan program that benefits private lenders
with an interest-rate subsidy.
</P>
<P>
Democrats support the direct lending program. They said the
bill should be a temporary relief measure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
