<HEADLINE> Confusion Over Albright's Comments on Settlements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Confusion over Israeli
settlements occurred today when Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright called Israeli settlements "legal" and the State
Department made a hasty statement that that does not mean any
reverse of U.S. policy on the issue.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview about Jewish settlement activity in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip, Albright said, "It's legal."
</P>
<P>
But her spokesman James Rubin said the secretary of state did
not intend to change U.S. policy, which for many years has
refrained from making a sweeping judgment on the status of
settlements under international law.
</P>
<P>
Her answer was "in the context of a discussion of what (the
1993) Oslo (peace agreement between Israel and Palestinians) does
and does not permit, not what the American position is on the
legality (under international Law) of settlements," Rubin said on
NBC television.
</P>
<P>
"All she meant by that was that as a technical matter, Oslo
does not prohibit the settlements.... We're talking here about
housing in Efrat (a West Bank city), we're not talking about new
settlements," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is clear: settlement activity is a complicating
factor and in several instances we have made clear that it's
unhelpful to creating an environment for peace talks," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
