<DOCNO> XIE19971002.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Dow industrials was pushed
back above 8,000 today as the first major September economic data
reinforced the belief in low inflation and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 70.24 points to 8,015.50,
the first finish above 8,000 since August 20. The blue-chip
barometer is up more than 24 percent in 1997, but still sits about
240 points below its August 6 peak of 8,259.31.
</P>
<P>
Several other stock indicators also set new highs as interest
rates fell toward their lowest level in more than one year in the
bond market.
</P>
<P>
Bonds rallied in the morning after a report about manufacturing
activity suggesting that inflationary pressures at the nation's
factories didn't worsen last month.
</P>
<P>
Smaller company shares extended their record-setting rally. The
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies closed at a record high
for the third straight session and 20th time in 25 sessions.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index, which is dominated
by secondary stocks, took its first-ever trip above 700, and the
New York Stock Exchange composite index, which has a large
constituency of smaller and mid-sized companies, closed above 500
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 597.89
million shares as against 586.79 million in the previous session.
</P>
</TEXT>
